(11, 'Breast lumps', '<h2>CAUSES</h2><h3>Discrete lumps:</h3><ul><li>Carcinoma</li><li>Phylloides tumour</li><li>Sarcoma - rare</li><li>Lymphoma  - rare</li><li>Fibroadenoma</li><li>Cyst - in cystic mastitis</li><li>Galactocele</li><li>Fat necrosis - rare</li><li>Lipoma</li><li>Duct ectasia</li><li>Tuberculous abscess - rare</li><li>Chronic pyogenic abscess</li><li>Sebaceous cyst</li><li>Plasma cell mastitis</li></ul><h3>Generalised swelling:</h3><ul><li>Pregnancy</li><li>Lactation</li><li>Puberty</li><li>Mastitis</li></ul><h3>Whole breast - bilateral:</h3><ul><li>Pregnancy</li><li>Lactation</li><li>ANDI (abnormalities of normal development and involution)</li><li>Hypertrophy</li><li>In males - from stilboestrol administration</li><li>Acute mastitis</li><li>Chronic interstitial mastitis (Fibroadenosis)</li></ul><h3>Whole breast - unilateral:</h3><ul><li>Fibroadenosis of the newborn</li><li>Puberty</li><li>Unilateral hypertrophy</li></ul><h3>Multiple swellings involving both breast:</h3><ul><li>ANDI</li><li>Multiple cysts</li></ul><h3>Swellings behind or not of the breast:</h3><ul><li>Retromammary abscess from chest disease</li><li>Tietze''s disease</li><li>Rib deformities</li><li>Chondroma of the costal cartilages or chest wall</li><li>Mondor''s disease</li></ul><h2>HISTORY</h2><ul><li>Carcinoma  - a strong family history, nulliparous state, early menarche, late menopause, history of cystic hyperplasia, patient may have found a breast lump or may have noticed nipple retraction, skin dimpling, axillary swelling</li><li>Carcinoma is painless in 85% of cases, stony hard and irregular in outline</li><li>Jaundice due to liver secondaries or porta hepatis node involvement</li><li>Bone pain due to secondary deposits and pathological fractures</li><li>Breathlessness due to lung secondaries or a pleural effusion</li><li>Personality change, fits, headaches - cerebral metastases</li><li>A patient who presents in pregnancy or lactation may have mastitis, abscess or galactocele</li><li>History of trauma - may be fat necrosis</li><li>A patient in the fifth decade with retroareolar pain, nipple retraction and a thick, creamy nipple discharge - duct ectasia</li><li>Patient between the ages of 15 and 25 with a non-tender, hard or soft swelling, moving freely, not fixed to any structure, no enlargement of lymph nodes - fibroadenoma</li><li>A patient with a history of painful breasts may have carcinoma, cyclical mastalgia, duct ectasia, fat necrosis, breast abscess, pregnancy, lactation, mastitis, Tietze''s disease, Mondor''s disease, rib secondaries or herpes zoster</li><li>Obtain past history of TB, if any since rarely a tuberculous abscess may form within the breast or erode through the chest wall from the lung</li><li>Acute mastitis - usually occurs during lactation, breast becomes painful, swollen and tender, skin over it becomes pinkish</li><li>Acute abscess - throbbing pain, oedema and fluctuation</li><li>Chronic pyogenic abscess - a painful lump, nipple may be retracted and there may be discharge of pus</li><li>Chronic interstitial mastitis (Fibroadenosis) - pain aggravates during menses,mass felt between finger and thumb is granular or knotty, axillary lymph nodes may be just enlarged, they are free from skin or deep fascia</li><li>Paget''s disease - malignant growth developing within breast near to nipple, ultimate disappearance of nipple leaving a flat bright red ulcer</li></ul><h2>EXAMINATION</h2><ul><li>Examine both breasts. Seat the woman at 45 degree supported on a couch. Contour of breast, skin changes, arm swelling are checked. The woman is asked to point to or find the lump, place her hand on the side being examined behind head and each quadrant of the breast is palpated with a flat hand, tail of the breast in the axilla is checked.</li><li>If a lump is found assess shape, size, surface, edge, consistency, mobility and attachments. Check local LNs in axilla and supraclavicular region and hepatomegaly</li></ul><h3>Carcinoma:</h3><ul><li>Usual age - 30-90, most common over 50 in middle-aged and elderly women</li><li>Number - usually single, although may coexist with other nodules</li><li>Shape - irregular or stellate</li><li>Consistency - firm or hard</li><li>Delimitation - not clearly delineated from surrounding tissues</li><li>Mobility - may be fixed to skin or underlying tissues</li><li>Tenderness - usually nontender</li><li>Retraction signs - may be present</li><li>Hard irregular swelling, may be fixed to the skin or fixed deeply</li><li>Skin dimpling, nipple retraction, Peau d''orange</li><li>Paget''s disease of the nipple</li><li>Axillary lymphadenopathy</li><li>Supraclavicular lymphadenopathy</li><li>Hepatomegaly</li></ul><h3>Phylloides tumour:</h3><ul><li>Mobile mass which may become very large</li></ul><h3>Fibroadenoma:</h3><ul><li>Usual age - 15-25, usually puberty and young adulthood</li><li>Number - usually single, may be multiple</li><li>Shape - round, disclike or lobular</li><li>Consistency - may be soft, usually firm</li><li>Delimitation - well delineated</li><li>Mobility - very mobile</li><li>Tenderness -  usually nontender</li><li>Retraction signs - absent</li><li>Smooth, rounded, mobile non tender mass, breast ''mouse'' (because it darts about under the examining fingers)</li></ul><h3>Lactating adenoma:</h3><ul><li>Pregnancy or lactation</li></ul><h3>Cyst:</h3><ul><li>Usual age -  30-50, regress after menopause except with estrogen therapy</li><li>Number - single or multiple</li><li>Shape - round</li><li>Consistency - soft to firm, usually elastic</li><li>Delimitation - well delineated</li><li>Mobility - mobile</li><li>Tenderness - often tender</li><li>Retraction signs - absent</li><li>Smooth, round, mobile swelling, may be tender, may be associated with generalised lumpiness of the breast</li></ul><h3>Fibrocystic disease:</h3><ul><li>Nodular, ropelike</li></ul><h3>Galactocele:</h3><ul><li>Smooth, mobile swelling occurring in the lactating breast</li></ul><h3>Fat necrosis:</h3><ul><li>Hard, irregular swelling, overlying bruising of the skin or teeth marks</li><li>The lesion is fixed to the skin and is difficult to distinguish from carcinoma occasionally</li></ul><h3>Lipoma:</h3><ul><li>Soft, lobulated swelling, rare in the breast</li><li>Pseudolipoma - a bunching of fat between retracted suspensory ligaments of the breast associated with an underlying carcinoma</li></ul><h3>Duct ectasia:</h3><ul><li>Tender retroareolar area</li><li>Retroareolar erythema</li><li>Nipple retraction</li><li>Thick, creamy nipple discharge</li></ul><h3>Sebaceous cyst:</h3><ul><li>Mobile swelling fixed to the skin, may have a punctum</li><li>May be infected, with discharge and surrounding redness</li></ul><h3>Generalised swellings:</h3><ul><li>Occur in pregnancy, lactation and puberty, also with mastitis (when the breast is enlarged, red, tender and hot)</li></ul><h3>Swellings behind the breast:</h3><ul><li>Tietze''s disease - prominence and tenderness over the second, third and fourth costal cartilages</li><li>Retromammary abscess - chest signs may be obvious on percussion and also on auscultation of the chest</li></ul><h2>INVESTIGATIONS</h2><h3>FBC:</h3><ul><li>Hb decreased  - widespread malignancy</li><li>increased WCC - breast abscess</li></ul><h3>ESR:</h3><ul><li>Increased - malignancy and tuberculosis</li></ul><h3>LFTs:</h3><ul><li>Alkaline phosphatase increased with liver secondaries and bone secondaries (isoenzymes)</li></ul><h3>Serum calcium:</h3><ul><li>Increased - bone secondaries</li></ul><h3>Chest X-ray:</h3><ul><li>Secondary deposits in lung and rib</li><li>Underlying chest disease - TB or empyema</li></ul><h3>FNAC:</h3><ul><li>Benign versus malignant</li><li>Cystic versus solid</li></ul><h3>Mammography:</h3><ul><li>Infiltrating radio-opaque mass or microcalcification indicates malignancy</li><li>Dilated retroareolar ducts and skin indentation - duct ectasia</li><li>Coarse calcification may occur with longstanding fibroadenomas</li></ul><h3>Open excision biopsy:</h3><ul><li>Fibroadenoma</li><li>Fat necrosis</li></ul><h3>Ultrasound:</h3><ul><li>US of breast better than mammography in young women</li><li>US of liver for metastases</li></ul><h3>CT scan:</h3><ul><li>Abdomen</li><li>Chest</li><li>Brain</li><li>Metastases</li></ul><h3>Bone scan:</h3><ul><li>Metastases</li></ul><h2>TREATMENT</h2><ul><li>No lump - reassure. Ask to check her own breasts and review in 6wk</li><li>Discrete lump - referral to surgeon. Asymmetrical nodularity. If less than 35y. old with family history  of breast cancer or  more than 35 y refer</li><li>If less than 35y and no family history review in 6wk - if the nodularity has gone reassure else refer</li></ul>', 'B'),
(12, 'Breast pain', '<h2>CAUSES</h2><ul><li>Carcinoma (15% of lumps are painful)</li><li>Cyclical mastalgia - in the week preceding a menstruation - fibroadenosis, cystic mastitis</li><li>Duct ectasia</li><li>Fat necrosis</li><li>Breast abscess</li><li>Pregnancy</li><li>Lactation</li><li>Tietze''s disease</li><li>Mondor''s disease</li><li>Rib secondaries</li><li>Herpes zoster</li><li>Onset of puberty</li><li>Cracked nipple</li><li>Inflammation of the nipple</li><li>Cyst of the breast</li><li>Galactocele</li><li>Submammary abscess</li><li>Mastitis, acture mastitis, periductal</li><li>Epithelioma of the nipple</li><li>Tuberculous disease of the breast</li><li>The after-effects of a blow or injury</li><li>Anxiety state</li><li>Angina</li><li>Cervical spondylosis</li></ul><h2>HISTORY</h2><ul><li>Cyclical mastalgia - soreness, frequently in the upper and outer quadrants of the breast in the week preceding a period, disappears after the period, freedom from soreness of pain for 2 weeks till it recommences, common in the 20-45 year age group</li><li>Duct ectasia - seen in the fifth decade, pain usually behind the nipple and associated with subareolar erythema and a thick, creamy nipple discharge</li><li>Fat necrosis - a history of trauma, which may be due to the partner''s teeth that the patient will be embarrassed to admit</li><li>Breast abscess or mastitis - usually during pregnancy or lactation but may occur in a retroareolar position in a patient with duct ectasia</li><li>Breast fullness and soreness is a symptom of early pregnancy, there may be breast pain where the condition is not actively in the breast but behind it</li><li>Tietze''s disease (costochronditis of the costal cartilages) - pain related to the breast</li><li>Mondor''s disease (superficial thrombophlebitis of the subcutaneous veins of the chest wall) -  pain in the breast, may be associated with an underlying carcinoma</li><li>Rib secondaries - pain behind the breast</li><li>Herpes zoster - pain radiating round into the breast and precedes the development of a vesicular eruption by 2-3 days</li></ul><h2>EXAMINATION</h2><ul><li>Examine both breasts. Seat the woman at 45 degree supported on a couch. Contour of breast, skin changes, arm swelling are checked. The woman is asked to point to or find the lump, place her hand on the side being examined behind head and each quadrant of the breast is palpated with a flat hand, tail of the breast in the axilla is checked.</li><li>If a lump is found assess shape, size, surface, edge, consistency, mobility and attachments. Check local LNs in axilla and supraclavicular region and hepatomegaly</li><li>Hard, irregular lump - carcinoma (this is discussed in the section on breast lumps</li><li>Tenderness and lumpiness, occasionally with a smooth, mobile swelling (cyst) - cyclical mastalgia</li><li>Tenderness and lumpiness is most often palpated in the upper and outer quadrants of the breast</li><li>Fat necrosis - bruising over the breast, tender lump in early stages, later it becomes hard and irregular and may be tethered to the skin</li><li>Breast abscess - redness, swelling, heat and pain in the breast during pregnancy or, more commonly, lactation, swelling will be fluctuant and usually with fever</li><li>Duct ectasia - subareolar erythema, tenderness and occasionally a subareolar lump, nipple retraction may be present in long-standing cases with a thick, creamy discharge that can be expressed from the nipple</li><li>Pregnancy - fullness of the breast and increased circumareolar pigmentation</li><li>Tietze''s disease - tenderness, and occasionally swelling, over the second, third and fourth costal cartilages</li><li>Mondor''s disease - the veins of the chest wall are felt as red, tender cords, often extending on to the anterior axillary fold</li><li>Carefully check the breast for an underlying mass, as the condition may be associated with carcinoma of the breast</li><li>Herpes zoster - characteristic vesicular eruption a few days after the pain</li></ul><h2>INVESTIGATIONS</h2><h3>FBC:</h3><ul><li>WCC increased - mastitis and breast abscess</li></ul><h3>ESR:</h3><ul><li>Increased - widespread carcinoma</li></ul><h3>LFTs :</h3><ul><li>Alkaline phosphatase may be raised with liver or bony secondaries</li></ul><h3>Serum calcium:</h3><ul><li>May be raised with bone secondaries</li></ul><h3>Swab:</h3><ul><li>Culture and sensitivity if there is any discharge from an abscess or from the nipple</li></ul><h3>Chest X-ray:</h3><ul><li>Secondaries in lung or ribs</li><li>Pleural effusion in carcinoma</li></ul><h3>Beta HCG:</h3><ul><li>Positive in - pregnancy</li></ul><h3>FNAC:</h3><ul><li>Benign versus malignant</li><li>Cystic versus solid</li></ul><h3>Mammography:</h3><ul><li>Carcinoma</li><li>Duct ectasia</li></ul><h3>Breast biopsy:</h3><ul><li>Benign versus malignant</li></ul><h3>Bone scan:</h3><ul><li>Rib secondaries</li><li>Myeloma</li></ul><h2>TREATMENT</h2><h3>Cyclical pain with or without nodularity:</h3><ul><li>If mild/moderate - reassure, advise simple analgesia or  OTC NSAID prn</li><li>If severe (15%) with pain more than 7days and interfering with life -  try gamolenic acid 240&mdash; 320mg daily for 6min(after 6min. stop and see what happens - pain recurs in 50% though often milder and not requiring treatment) if severe pain recurs treat again</li><li>If gamolenic acid fails discontinue any oral contraceptives and if pain persists try either danazol (200-300mg daily for Imin. then l00mg daily for 5min.) or bromocriptine</li></ul><h3>Non-cyclical pain:</h3><ul><li>Mild or moderate&mdash; reassure. If severe (-50%) assess whether localized or diffuse</li><li>If localized -  refer</li><li>If diffuse - try NSAID or, if ineffective, gamolenic acid, danazol or bromocriptine</li><li>Refer if persistent or refractory to treatment.</li></ul>', 'B'),
(13, 'Bullae (Blisters)', '<ul><li>Trauma - friction, thermal, caustic</li><li>Insect bites</li><li>Jelly-fish</li><li>Dermatitis artefacta</li><li>Bullous impetigo</li><li>Lyell''s syndrome</li><li>Eczema - contact dermatitis, pompholyx</li><li>Fixed drug eruption</li><li>Erythema multiforme</li><li>Porphyria'' cutanea tarda</li><li>Epidermolysis bullosa</li><li>Pemphigus</li><li>Pemphigoid</li><li>Dermatitis herpetiformis</li></ul>', 'B'),
(14, 'Buttock pain', '<h2>CAUSES</h2><ul><li>Sacroiliitis - spondyloarthropathies</li><li>Infection - tuberculous or pyogenic</li><li>Primary and secondary tumours of pelvic bones</li><li>Pelvic fracture (especially due to osteoporosis in the elderly)</li><li>Osteomalacia</li><li>Paget''s disease of bone</li><li>Polymyaigh rheumatica</li><li>Gluteal or trochanteric bursitis</li></ul>', 'B'),
(15, 'Calf pain', '<h2>CAUSES</h2><ul><li>Deep venous thrombosis - doppler techniquue or venography</li><li>Ruptured Baker''s cyst - arthrography or ultrasound</li><li>Intermittent claudication</li><li>Referral from the lumbar spine (sciatica)</li><li>Psychological</li><li>Spasticity</li></ul>', 'C'),
(16, 'Cataract', '<h2>CAUSES</h2><h3>Senile cataract:</h3><h3>Cataract associated with ocular disease:</h3><ul><li>Uveitis</li><li>Glaucoma</li><li>Neoplasia</li><li>Tropical drug therapy - steroids and miotics</li><li>Trauma - mechanical, chemical or radiation</li></ul><h3>Cataract associated with systemic disease:</h3><ul><li>Rubella</li><li>Cytomegalovirus</li><li>Toxoplasmosis</li><li>Down''s syndrome</li><li>Turner''s syndrome</li><li>Marfan''s syndrome</li><li>Steroids</li><li>Antimitotics</li><li>Chlorpromazine</li><li>Diabetes mellitus</li><li>Galactosaemia</li><li>Mannosidosis</li><li>Fabry''s disease</li><li>Lowes syndrome</li><li>Wilson''s disease</li><li>Hypocalcaemia (hypoparathyroidism)</li><li>Myotonia dystrophica</li><li>Atopic dermatitis</li><li>Ichthyosis</li></ul>', 'C'),
(17, 'Cervical abnormalities', '<h2>CARCINOMA OF CERVIX</h2><ul><li>Carcinoma of the cervix begins in an area of metaplasia. In its earliest stages, it cannot be distinguished from a normal cervix. In a late stage, an extensive, irregular, cauliflowerlike growth may develop. Early frequent intercourse, multiple partners, smoking, and infection with human papillomavirus increase the risk for cervical cancer</li></ul><h2>CERVICAL POLYP</h2><ul><li>A cervical polyp usually arises from the endocervical canal, becoming visible when it protrudes through the cervical os. It is bright red, soft, and rather fragile. When only the tip is seen, it cannot be differentiated clinically from a polyp originating in the endometrium. Polyps are benign but may bleed</li></ul><h3>FOETAL EXPOSURE TO DIETHYLSTILBESTROL (DES):</h3><ul><li>Daughters of women who took DES during pregnancy are at much higher risk for a number of abnormalities, including columnar epithelium that covers most or all of the cervix, vaginal adenosis, extension of this epithelium to the vaginal wall, and a circular collar or ridge of tissue, of varying shapes, between cervix and vagina. Much less common is an otherwise rare carcinoma of the upper vagina</li></ul><h2>MUCOPURULENT CERVICITIS</h2><ul><li>Mucopurulent cervicitis produces purulent yellow drainage from the cervical os, usually due to infection from Chlamydia trachomatis, Neisseria gonorrhoeae, or herpes. These infections are sexually transmitted, and may occur without symptoms or signs</li></ul><h2>RETENTION CYSTS</h2><ul><li>With increasing estrogen stimulation during adolescence, all or part of this columnar epithelium is transformed into squamous epithelium by a process termed metaplasia</li><li>This change may block the secretions of columnar epithelium and cause retention cysts (sometimes called nabothian cysts). These appear as one or more translucent nodules on the cervical surface and have no pathologic significance</li></ul>', 'C');
