(18, 'Dysphagia', '<h3>Congential:</h3><ul><li>Oesophageal atresia</li></ul><h3>Acquired:</h3><ul><li>Food bolus</li><li>Foreign body</li><li>Inflammatory stricture  - gastro-oesophgeal reflux, caustic stricture, candidiasis</li><li>Achalasia</li><li>Carcinoma</li><li>Plummer-Vinson syndrome</li><li>Irradiation</li><li>Scleroderma</li><li>Chagas'' disease (rare)</li><li>Pharygeal pouch</li><li>Mediastinal tumours - bronchial carcinoma,</li><li>Enlarged left atrium (mitral stenosis)</li><li>Aortic aneurysm</li><li>Paraoesophageal (rolling) hiatus hernia</li><li>Dysphagia lusoria (rare)</li><li>Bulbar palsy</li><li>Guillain-Barre syndrome</li><li>CVA</li><li>Motor neurone disease</li><li>Myasthenia gravis</li></ul><h3>Common :</h3><ul><li>Foreign body, acute oesophagitis, and simple stricture</li><li>Tumour pressing oesophagus from outside</li><li>Achalasia cardia</li><li>Cancer of oesophagus</li><li>Plummer-Vinson syndrome</li></ul><h3>Less common:</h3><ul><li>Functional dysphagia</li><li>Paralysis of pharynx</li><li>Congenital atresia and short oesophagus</li><li>Carcinoma</li><li>Aberrant vessel</li><li>Congenital web (plummer - vinson syndrome)</li><li>Cervical osteophytes</li><li>Cricopharyngeal achalasia</li><li>Hypertensive or hypotensive upper oesophageal sphincter</li><li>Zenker''s diverticulum</li><li>Myasthenia gravis</li><li>Steroid myopathy</li><li>Hyperthyroidism</li><li>Hypothyroidism</li><li>Myotonic dystrophy</li><li>Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis</li><li>Multiple sclerosis</li><li>Parkinsonism</li><li>Bulbar and pseudobulbar palsy</li><li>Intermittent - lower oesophageal ring</li><li>Progressive - peptic strictures (with heart burn), carcinoma (no heart burn)</li></ul><h2>HISTORY</h2><h3>Congenital:</h3><ul><li>Associated with maternal polyhydramnios, newborn baby showingdribbing of saliva, inability to swallow feeds, production of frothy mucus, choking attacks, cyanotic attacks and chest infections</li></ul><h3>Acquired:</h3><ul><li>History of ingestion of a foreign body (a coin in children), false teeth in elderly</li><li>Caustic stricture - history of caustic ingestion, except in the psychiatrically disturbed, where the history may not be apparent</li><li>Caustic stricture - sudden onset of pain and dysphagia, which may improve with appropirate treatment only to recur after several months due to a stricture</li><li>Inflammatory stricture due to gastro-oesophageal reflux associated with a hiatus hernia - a history of retrosternal burning pain and acid reflux worse on recumbency or bending down, gradual onset and the patient may localise the site of dysphagia to the level of the lower end of the sternum</li><li>Oesophageal candidiasis - dysphagia  in the immunocompromised patient</li><li>Achalasia - degeneration of the oesophageal myenteric plexus resulting in loss oesophageal sphincter to relax in response to swallowing, presents between 30 and 50 years of age, intermittent dysphagia getting progressively worse, worse for liquids than for solids</li><li>Achalasia - food is felt to stick at the lower end of the oesophagus and pain may be felt behind xiphisternum</li><li>Fluid regurgitation at night may result in aspiration pneumonitis</li><li>Carcinoma - dysphagia is of rapid onset, initially for solids, then for fluids with weight loss, anorexia and symptoms of anaemia, history of achalasia or Barrett''s oesophagus</li><li>Carcinoma oesophagus - dysphagia is a late symptom of cancer oesophagus, but dysphagia becomes steadily and progressively worse, vomit contains mucus and streaks of blood, when cervical oesophagus is involved a bout of cough brings out the food and weakness or loss of voice may occur from recurrent laryngeal paralysis.</li><li>Dysphagia with food sticking at the upper end of the oesophagus in a middle-aged female - Plummer-Vinson syndrome (web in the upper oesophagus - postcricoid web, premalignant)</li><li>A  history of radiotherapy to chest or mediastinum may suggest an irradiation stricture</li><li>Scleroderma changes in the skin, around the lips, in the fingers (sclerodactyly) or past history of Raynaud''s phenomenon</li><li>Chagas'' disease extremely rare and is associated with  degeneration of the myenteric plexus associated with trypanosomal infection, symptoms are identical  with those of achalasia</li><li>Pharyngeal pouch seen in middle age or elderly, a swelling,usually in the left posterior triangle of the neck, dysphagia localised behind the manubrium associated with the pouch pressing  on the oesophagus,  regurgitation of food with coughing on lying down,  halitosis</li><li>Bronchial carcinoma - direct pressure on the oesophagus from the tumour or via mediastinal lymp node secondaries or the patient may present with haemoptysis</li><li>Dysphagia from mediastinal lymphadenopathy - enlarged swellings at other sites - groins, axilla</li><li>Dysphagia from pressure of an enlarged left atrium - mitral stenosis, past history of mitral stenosis</li><li>Paraoesophageal (rolling) hernia - intetmittent dysphagia due to a full stomatch pressing on the adjacent oesophagus</li><li>Hiccups may occur due to irritation of the diaphragm</li><li>History of Guillain-Barre syndrome, poliomyelitis, motor neurone disease, myasthenia gravis or CVA</li></ul><h2>TRANSFER DYSPHAGIA</h2><h3>Timing:</h3><ul><li>Acute a gradual onset and a variable course, depending on the underlying disorder</li></ul><h3>Factors that aggravate:</h3><ul><li>Attempts to start the swallowing process</li></ul><h3>Associated symptoms and conditions:</h3><ul><li>Aspiration into the lungs or regurgitation into the nose with attempts to swallow. Neurologic evidence of stroke, bulbar palsy, or other neuro-muscular conditions</li></ul><h2>ESOPHAGEAL DYSPHAGIA</h2><h3>Timing:</h3><ul><li>Intermittent</li></ul><h3>Factors that aggravate:</h3><ul><li>Solid foods</li></ul><h3>Factors that relieve:</h3><ul><li>Regurgitation of the bolus of food</li></ul><h3>Associated symptoms and conditions:</h3><ul><li>Usually none</li></ul><h3>Timing:</h3><ul><li>Intermittent, may become slowly progressive</li></ul><h3>Factors that aggravate:</h3><ul><li>Solid foods</li></ul><h3>Factors that relieve:</h3><ul><li>Regurgitation of the bolus food</li></ul><h3>Associated symptoms and conditions:</h3><ul><li>A long history of heart- burn and regurgitation</li></ul><h3>Timing:</h3><ul><li>May be intermittent at first; progressive over months</li></ul><h3>Factors that aggravate:</h3><ul><li>Solid foods, with progression to liquids</li></ul><h3>Factors that relieve:</h3><ul><li>Regurgitation of the bolus  of food</li></ul><h3>Associated symptoms and conditions:</h3><ul><li>Pain in the chest and back and weight loss, especially late in the course of illness</li></ul><h3>Motor disorders:</h3><h3>Timing:</h3><ul><li>Intermittent</li></ul><h3>Factors that aggravate:</h3><ul><li>Solids or liquids</li></ul><h3>Factors that relieve:</h3><ul><li>Maneuvers described below; sometimes nitroglycerin</li></ul><h3>Associated symptoms and conditions:</h3><ul><li>Chest pain that mimics angina pectoris or myocardial infarction and lasts minutes to hours, possibly heartburn</li></ul><h3>Timing:</h3><ul><li>Intermittent, may progress slowly</li></ul><h3>Factors that aggravate:</h3><ul><li>Solids or liquids</li></ul><h3>Factors that relieve:</h3><ul><li>Repeated swallowing, movements such as straightening the back, raising the arms, or a Valsalva maneuver (straining down against a closed glottis)</li></ul><h3>Associated symptoms and conditions:</h3><ul><li>Heart burn . Other manifestations of scleroderma</li><li>Regurgitation, often at night when lying down, with nocturnal cough; possibly chest pain precipitated by eating</li></ul><h3>Timing:</h3><ul><li>Intermittent, may progress</li></ul><h3>Factors that aggravate:</h3><ul><li>Solids or liquids</li></ul><h3>Factors that relieve:</h3><ul><li>Repeated Swallowing, movements such as straightening the back, raising the arms, or a Valsalva maneuver (straining down against a closed glottis)</li></ul><h3>Associated symptoms and conditions:</h3><ul><li>Heart burn . Other manifestations of scleroderma</li><li>Regurgitation, often at night when lying down, with nocturnal cough; possibly chest pain precipitated by eating</li></ul><h2>EXAMINATION</h2><ul><li>Passage of orogastric tube in oesophageal atresia</li><li>Pharyngeal pouch - palpable swelling low down in the posterior triangle of the neck (usually left), which gurgles on palpation</li><li>Carcinoma - signs of weight loss, a palpable liver due to metastases, or cervical lymphadenopathy due to metastases</li><li>Plummer-Vinson syndrome - koilonychia, angular cheilitis ans glossitis</li><li>Irradiation stricture - changes in the skin consistent with previous radiotherapy</li><li>Scleroderma - calcinosis of the subcutaneous tissue, Raynaud''s phenomenon, sclerodactyly and telangiectasis</li><li>Dydphagia due to an enlarged left atrium in mitral stenosis - signs of mitral stenosis like peripheral cyanosis, malar flush, left parasternal heave, tapping apex beat, opening snap and mid-diastolic murmur best heard at the apex</li></ul><h2>INVESTIGATIONS</h2><h3>FBC:</h3><ul><li>Hb decreased - carcinoma but may also occurs with oesophagitis associated with peotic strictures, anaemia may also be associated with Plummer-Vinson syndrome</li></ul><h3>ESR:</h3><ul><li>Increased - malignancy and scleroderma</li></ul><h3>U&Es:</h3><ul><li>Dehydration</li></ul><h3>LFTs:</h3><ul><li>Alkaline phosphatase increased - liver secondaries</li></ul><h3>Chest X-ray:</h3><ul><li>Radio-opaque - foreign body</li><li>Air-fluid level - achalasia</li><li>Gastric air bubble in chest -paraoesophageal hernia</li><li>Hilar lymphadenopathy</li><li>Bronchial carcinoma</li><li>Widened mediastrium with aortic aneurysm</li><li>Large left atrium (double shadow behind the heart) - mitral stenosis</li><li>Mediastinal mass</li><li>Plueral effusion</li><li>Aspiration pneumonia</li><li>Secondary lung abscess</li></ul><h3>ECG:</h3><ul><li>Left artrial hypertrophy</li></ul><h3>Barium swallow:</h3><ul><li>Pharyngeal pouch (never OGD as it may perforate the pouch), stricture, achalasia, external compression</li><li>Benign stricture - Smooth narrowing with no evidence ofmu cosal irregularity</li><li>Achalasia - smooth beak like narrowing of distal oesophageal segment. Air fluid level may be observed.</li><li>Hiatus hernia and oesophagitis - presence ofgastro-oesophageal reflux and secondary changes of oesophagitis. Lately ulcers may be seen.</li><li>Carcinoma oesophagus - Irregular and often long luminal defect indicates malignancy. Sometimes the tumor may be circumferential, ring like constriction but some where it will be irregular.</li><li>Oesophageal motor abnormalities - aperistaltic oesophagus</li><li>Endoscopy - (for direct visualization)</li><li>Cytology - biopsy</li><li>Motility studies (manometric recording)</li></ul><h3>OGD (Oesophago gastro-dudenoscopy):</h3><ul><li>Foreign body</li><li>Food bolus</li><li>Candidiasis</li><li>Benign versus malignant stricture</li><li>Plummer-Vinson syndrome - postcricoid web</li><li>Biopsy- benign lesions versus malignant lesion, absence of myenteric plexus in achalasia</li></ul><h3>CT scan:</h3><ul><li>Mediastinal nodes</li><li>Spread of malignancy</li><li>Tumour staging</li><li>Aortic aneurysm</li><li>Dysphagia lusoria (abnormally placed arteries causing external compression)</li></ul>', 'D'),
(19, 'Dyspnoea', '<h2>CAUSES</h2><h3>Sudden (seconds - minutes):</h3><ul><li>Pneumothorax</li><li>Pulmonary oedema</li><li>Pulmonary embolism</li><li>Aspiration</li><li>Anaphylaxis</li><li>Anxiety</li><li>Chest trauma</li></ul><h3>Acute (hours - days):</h3><ul><li>Asthma</li><li>Respiratory tract infection</li><li>Lung tumours</li><li>Pleural effusion</li><li>Metabolic acidosis</li><li>Pneumonia</li></ul><h3>Chronic (months - years) :</h3><ul><li>Chronic airflow limitation (COPD)</li><li>Cardiac failure</li><li>Fibrosing alveolitis</li><li>Anaemia</li><li>Arrhythmia</li><li>Valvular heart disease</li><li>Chest wall deformities</li><li>Neuromuscular disorders</li><li>Cystic fibrosis</li><li>Pulmonary hypertension</li></ul><h3>Excessive ventilation:</h3><ul><li>Cyanotic congenital heart diseases</li><li>Diabetic ketosis</li><li>Severe anaemia</li><li>Dyspnoea of mountaineers</li><li>Arterial hypoxaemia</li><li>Respiratory distress syndrome of the new born</li><li>Pyrexia</li><li>Acidosis of renal failure</li></ul><h3>Reduced ventilatory capacity:</h3><ul><li>Obstructive lung diseases - bronchial and bronchiolar narrowing</li><li>Chronic bronchitis</li><li>Bronchiectasis</li><li>Emphysema</li><li>Bronchial asthma</li><li>Pulmonary fibrosis</li><li>Lobar collapse</li></ul><h3>Obstructive ventilatory defects:</h3><ul><li>Chronic obstructive airways disease</li><li>Emphysema</li><li>Asthma</li><li>Bronchiectasis</li><li>Cystic fibrosis</li><li>Byssinosis</li><li>Upper airways obstruction (uncommon)</li></ul><h3>Restrictive lung diseases:</h3><ul><li>Extensive pulmonary resection</li><li>Pleural effusion</li><li>Spontaneous pnuemothorax</li><li>Kyphoscoliosis</li><li>Sternal depression</li><li>Fibrosing alveolitis</li><li>Sarcoidosis</li><li>Extrinsic allergic alveolitis</li><li>Pneumoconioses</li><li>Chest wall deformity</li><li>Pulmonary oedema</li><li>Left ventricular dysfunction</li></ul><h3>Restrictive ventilatory defects, uncommon causes:</h3><ul><li>Large tumours</li><li>Large hiatus hernia</li><li>Lymphangitis carcinomatosa</li><li>Connective tissue diseases</li><li>Aspiration pneumonitis</li><li>Infections</li></ul><h3>Psychogenic dyspnoea:</h3><ul><li>Tension and pressure of anxiety</li><li>Depression</li></ul><h3>Cardiac asthma:</h3><ul><li>Elevated pulmonary capillary pressure</li><li>Heart failure</li></ul><h3>Uncommon causes:</h3><ul><li>Acidosis</li><li>Pregnancy</li><li>Cyanotic congenital heart  disease</li><li>High altitude</li><li>Arteriovenous fistula</li></ul><h3>Conditions associated with decreased neuromuscular power:</h3><ul><li>Myasthenia gravis</li><li>Polyneuritis</li><li>Poliomyelitis</li><li>Motor neurone disease</li><li>Muscular dystrophies</li></ul><h2>HISTORY</h2><h3>Dyspnoea with drowsiness:</h3><ul><li>Renal failure</li><li>Diabetic ketoacidosis</li><li>Methyl alcohol poisoning</li><li>Severe hypoxia</li><li>Drug induced (morphine)</li><li>Hypertensive encephalopathy</li><li>Embolic stroke</li></ul><h3>Dyspnoea with pulmonary cause:</h3><ul><li>Cough/expectoration/wheeze</li><li>Fever</li><li>Chest pain (pleural type)</li><li>Weight loss</li><li>Progressive increase over years</li><li>Immediate relief with bronchodilators</li><li>Good response to oxygenation</li><li>Presence of cyanosis in adults</li></ul><h3>Dyspnoea with cardiac cause:</h3><ul><li>Paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnoea</li><li>Orthopnoea</li><li>Clinical signs of heart disease</li><li>Brown, rusty sputum</li><li>Rapid progression</li><li>Little or no cyanosis with severe dyspnoea</li><li>Response to diuretics and digoxin</li><li>Cheyne - stokes breathing</li></ul><h3>Paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnoea:</h3><ul><li>Return ofoedematous fluid from the dependant part to systemic circulation, to right ventricle, overfilling the lungs</li><li>Decrease in sympathetic drive, during sleep, decreasing left ventricular contractility</li><li>Sleep induced dreams and subsequent increase in emotional activities</li><li>Nocturnal arrhythmias</li></ul><h3>Excessive ventilation:</h3><ul><li>Cyanotic congenital heart diseases - severe hypoxaemia and consequent dyspnoea  relieved by sqatting, specially in children</li><li>Acidosis - increased ventilation as in diabetic ketosis</li><li>Severe anaemia - dyspnoea due to anaerobic muscle metabolism during exercise</li><li>The dyspnoea of mountaineers - hypoxia</li><li>Arterial hypoxaemia - increased exercise ventilation, hypoxaemia which can be corrected by oxygen inhalation</li></ul><h3>Reduced ventilatory capacity:</h3><ul><li>Obstructive lung disease - bronchial and bronchiolar narrowing</li><li>Chronic bronchitis - production of mucoid or purulent cough more than 3 months each year</li><li>Bronchiectasis - dyspnoea depending upon the extent of bronchitis, early morning production of copius purulent sputum and haemoptysis along with clubbing of nails</li><li>Emphysema - progressive dyspnoea, chest becomes over inflated producing barrel-chest</li><li>Bronchial asthma - acute obstructive ventilatory defect which can be relieved by bronchodilators</li></ul><h3>Restrictive lung diseases:</h3><ul><li>Fibrosing alveolitis - dyspnoea on exertion, unproductive cough, vague chest pains and cyanosis</li><li>Dyspnoea is not an early symptom of carcinoma of lung or of pulmonary tuberculosis</li><li>Pulmonary oedema is a well known hazard of infusion of saline which results in dyspnoea</li></ul><h3>Psychogenic dyspnoea:</h3><ul><li>Tension and pressure of anxiety may result in dyspnoea</li><li>Depression causes irregular breathing which returns to normal during sleep</li></ul><h3>Cardiac asthma:</h3><ul><li>Exertional dyspnoea occurs most commonly as a consequence of an elevated pulmonary capillary pressure, usually begins as breathlessness on strenuous exertion and over the course of months and years sets in dyspnoea at rest</li><li>Dyspnoea in the lying down position - heart failure associated with elevation of pulmonary venous and capillary pressures</li></ul><h3>Precipitating factors:</h3><ul><li>Trauma - fractured ribs or a pneumothorax</li><li>Aspiration of a foreign body - determined from the history</li><li>Aspiration of vomit occurs in patients with decreased consciousness levels or who have lost the gag reflex</li><li>Occassionally patients may complain of waking up at right gasping for breath when they slide down the pillows - paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnoea</li><li>Dyspnoea associated with asthma may be seasonal (grass pollen) or perennial (house dust mite faecal proteins), depending on the precipitating allergen</li><li>History of severe allergy for consideration of anaphylaxis</li></ul><h3>Relieving factors:</h3><ul><li>Dyspnoea resulting from cardiac failure may be relieves by sitting upright, and when due to asthma, by beta agonists</li></ul><h3>Associated factors:</h3><ul><li>Cough productive of (green, yellow, rusty) sputum - chest infection, may be the primary cause or it may excerbate dysponea in patients with an existing condition such as asthma, COPD or cardiac failure</li><li>Bloodstained sputum - chest infection especially TB, pulmonary embolism or a tumour</li><li>Wheezing - asthma or aspiration of a foreign body</li></ul><h3>Process:</h3><ul><li>Elevated pressure in pumonary capillary bed with transudation of fluid into interstitial spaces and alveoli, decreased compliance (increased stiffness) of the lungs, increased work of breathing</li></ul><h3>Timing:</h3><ul><li>Dyspnea may progress slowly, or suddenly as in  acute pulmonary edema.</li></ul><h3>Factors that aggravate:</h3><ul><li>Exertion, lying down</li></ul><h3>Factors that relieve:</h3><ul><li>Rest, sittingup, though dyspnea may become persistent</li></ul><h3>Associated symptoms:</h3><ul><li>Often cough, orthopnea, paraoxysmal nocturnal dyspnea; sometimes wheezing</li></ul><h3>Setting:</h3><ul><li>History of heart disease or its predisposing factors</li></ul><h2>CHRONIC BRONCHITIS</h2><h3>Process:</h3><ul><li>Excessive mucus production in bronchi, followed by chronic obstruction of airways</li></ul><h3>Timing:</h3><ul><li>Chronic productive cough followed by slowly progressive dyspnea</li></ul><h3>Factors that aggravate:</h3><ul><li>Exertion, inhaled irritants, respiratory infections</li></ul><h3>Factors that relieve:</h3><ul><li>Expectoration; rest, though dyspnea may become persistent</li></ul><h3>Associated symptoms:</h3><ul><li>Chronic productive cough, recurrent repiratory infections; wheezing may develop</li></ul><h3>Setting:</h3><ul><li>History of smoking, air pollutants, recurrentt respiratory infections</li></ul><h3>Process:</h3><ul><li>Overdistention of air spaces distal to terminal bronchioles, with destruction of alveolar septa and chronic obstuction of the airways</li></ul><h3>Timing:</h3><ul><li>Slowly progressive dyspnea; relatively mild cough later</li></ul><h3>Factors that aggravate:</h3><ul><li>Exertion</li></ul><h3>Factors that relieve:</h3><ul><li>Rest, though dyspnea may become persistent</li></ul><h3>Associated symptoms:</h3><ul><li>Cough, with scant mucoid sputum</li></ul><h3>Setting:</h3><ul><li>History of smoking, air pollutants, sometimes a familial deficiency in alpha1-antitrypsin</li></ul><h2>ASTHMA</h2><h3>Process:</h3><ul><li>Bronchial hyperresponsiveness involving release of inflammatory mediators, increased airway secretions, and bronchoconstriction</li></ul><h3>Timing:</h3><ul><li>Acute episodes, separated by symptom-free periods. Nocturnal episodes are common.</li></ul><h3>Factors that aggravate:</h3><ul><li>Variable, including allergens, irritants, respiratory infections, exercise, and emotion</li></ul><h3>Factors that relieve:</h3><ul><li>Separation from aggravating factors</li></ul><h3>Associated symptoms:</h3><ul><li>Wheezing, cough, tightness in chest</li></ul><h3>Setting:</h3><ul><li>Environmental and emotional conditions</li></ul><h2>DIFFUSE INTERSTITIAL LUNG DISEASES</h2><h3>Process:</h3><ul><li>Abnormal and widespread infiltration of cells, fluid, and collagen into interstitial spaces between alveoli. Many causes</li></ul><h3>Timing:</h3><ul><li>Progressive dyspnea, which varies in its rate of development with the cause</li></ul><h3>Factors that aggravate:</h3><ul><li>Exertion</li></ul><h3>Factors that relieve:</h3><ul><li>Rest. though dyspnea may become persistent</li></ul><h3>Associated symptoms:</h3><ul><li>Often weaknessm fatigue. Cough less common than in other lung diseases</li></ul><h3>Setting:</h3><ul><li>Varied. Exposure to one of many substances may be causative.</li></ul><h2>PNEUMONIA</h2><h3>Process:</h3><ul><li>Inflammation of lung parenchyma from the respiratory bronchiles to the alveoli</li></ul><h3>Timing:</h3><ul><li>An acute illness, timing varies with tghe causative agent</li></ul><h3>Associated symptoms:</h3><ul><li>Pluritic pain, cough, sputum, fever, though not necessarily present</li></ul><h3>Setting:</h3><ul><li>Varied</li></ul><h2>SPONTANEOUS PNEUMOTHORAX</h2><h3>Process:</h3><ul><li>Leakage of air into pleural space through blebs on visceral pleura, with resulting partial or complete collapse of the lung</li></ul><h3>Associated symptoms:</h3><ul><li>Pleuritic pain, cough</li></ul><h3>Setting:</h3><ul><li>Often a previosuly healthy young adult</li></ul><h2>ACUTE PULMONARY EMBOLISM</h2><h3>Process:</h3><ul><li>Sudden occlusion of all or part of pulmonary arterial tree by a blood clot that usually originates in deep veins of legs or pelvis</li></ul><h3>Timing:</h3><ul><li>Sudden onset of dyspnea</li></ul><h3>Associated symptoms:</h3><ul><li>Often none. Retrosternal oppressive pain of the occlusion is massive. Pleuritic pain, cough, and hemoptysis may follow an embolism if pulmonary infarction ensues. Symptoms of anxiety</li></ul><h3>Setting:</h3><ul><li>Postpartum or postoperative periods; prolonged bed rest; congestive heart failure, chronic lung disease, and fractures of hip or leg; deep venous thrombosis (often not clinically apparent)</li></ul><h2>ANXIETY WITH HYPERVENTILATION</h2><h3>Process:</h3><ul><li>Overbreathing, with resultant respiratory alkalosis and fall in the partial pressure of carbon dioxide in the blood</li></ul><h3>Timing:</h3><ul><li>Episodic, often recurrent</li></ul><h3>Factors that aggravate:</h3><ul><li>More often occurs at rest than after exercise. An upsetting event may not be evident.</li></ul><h3>Factors that relieve:</h3><ul><li>Breathing in and out of a paper or plastic bag sometimes helps that associated symptoms.</li></ul><h3>Associated symptoms:</h3><ul><li>Sighing, lightheadedness, numbness or tingling of the hands and feet, palpitations, chest pain</li></ul><h3>Setting:</h3><ul><li>Other manifestations of anxiety may be present</li></ul><h2>RESPIRATORY CONDITIONS</h2><h3>Persistent bronchitis :</h3><ul><li>Cough - positive</li><li>Chest pain - positive</li><li>Wheezing - positive</li><li>Cyanosis - positive</li><li>Haemolysis or bloody sputum - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - hyperresonant percussion note; diminished vocal fremitus; rhonchi</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - no changes or prominent linear shadows with propgressive alterations in lung markings</li></ul><h3>Bronchiectasis :</h3><ul><li>Cough - positive</li><li>Wheezing - positive</li><li>Cyanosis - positive</li><li>Haemolysis or bloody sputum - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - weak breath sounds; diminished vocal fremitus, rhonchi, coarse crepitations</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - patchy consolidations ; increased bronchovascular markings.</li></ul><h3>Pneumonia :</h3><ul><li>Cough - positive</li><li>Chest pain - positive</li><li>Cyanosis - positive</li><li>Haemolysis or bloody sputum - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - impaired percussion note; crepitations; absent or diminished breath sounds.</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - consolidation in the lobe or in patchy distribution</li></ul><h3>Pleural effusion :</h3><ul><li>Cough - positive</li><li>Chest pain - positive</li><li>Cyanosis - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - stony dull percussion; diminished or absent breath sounds and vocal</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - homogeneous opacity; displaced mediastnum; obscured costophrenic angles; fluid in pleural spaces.</li></ul><h3>Pneumothorax :</h3><ul><li>Cough - positive</li><li>Chest pain - positive</li><li>Cyanosis - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - absent or diminished vocal fremitus and breath sounds; hyperresonance</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - sharp edge of collapsed lung; translucency with no lung marking; mediastinal displacement</li></ul><h3>Pulmonary emphysema :</h3><ul><li>Cough - positive</li><li>Wheezing - positive</li><li>Cyanosis - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - diffuse hyperresonance; scattered wheezes and rhonchi; diminished vocal fremitus</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - hypertranslucency of lung fields; widened intercoastal spaces;</li></ul><h3>Pulmonary tuberculosis :</h3><ul><li>Cough - positive</li><li>Chest pain - positive</li><li>Wheezing - positive</li><li>Haemolysis or bloody sputum - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - slightly increased percussion note at upper chest; weakened breath sounds</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - calcified and enlarged lymph nodes; consolidation with fibrosis</li></ul><h3>Bronchial asthma :</h3><ul><li>Cough - positive</li><li>Wheezing - positive</li><li>With or without cyanosis</li><li>Chest sounds - hyperresonant percussion note; diminished vocal fremitus; high pitched rhonchi</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - nothing or increased bronchovascular markings</li></ul><h3>Adult respiratory distress syndrome :</h3><ul><li>Cough - positive</li><li>Cyanosis - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - diminished breath sounds; coarse crepitations</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - diffuse bilateral alveolar infiltration; later, snow-storm appearance</li></ul><h3>Pulmonary eosinophilia :</h3><ul><li>Cough - positive</li><li>Chest pain - positive</li><li>Haemolysis or bloody sputum - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - hyperresonance, rhonchi and crepitations</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - localised or diffuse opacity</li></ul><h3>Diffuse fibrosing alveolitis :</h3><ul><li>Cough - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - prominent breath sounds; crackling crepitations</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - diffuse opacities; high diaphragm; later, honey comb appearance</li></ul><h3>Silicosis :</h3><ul><li>Cough - positive</li><li>Wheezing - positive</li><li>Haemolysis or bloody sputum - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - hyperresonant or dull percussion note; rhonchi</li><li>Chest X-ray findings -  nodular opacities; interstitial fibrosis; egg-shell opacities</li></ul><h2>CARDIAC CONDITIONS</h2><h3>Cor pulmonale :</h3><ul><li>Cough -  positive</li><li>Chest pain - positive</li><li>Wheezing - positive</li><li>Cyanosis -  positive</li><li>Haemolysis or bloody sputum -  positive</li><li>Chest sounds - crepitant rales over lung base; diminished breath sounds</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - enlargement of right ventricle and pulmonary artery; increased bronchovascular markings</li></ul><h3>Cardiac failure :</h3><ul><li>Cough -  positive</li><li>Wheezing - positive</li><li>Cyanosis -  positive</li><li>Haemolysis or bloody sputum - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - accentuated pulmonary second sound; basal crepitations; sometimes rhonchi.</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - enlargement of right ventricle and pulmonary artery; increased bronchovascular markings</li></ul><h3>Myocardial infarction :</h3><ul><li>Chest pain - positive</li><li>Cyanosis - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - soft systolic blowing murmur; presystolic or systolic gallop rhythm</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - notching or enlarged cardiac shadow, pulmonary oedema</li></ul><h3>Mitral stenosis :</h3><ul><li>Cough - positive</li><li>Haemolysis or bloody sputum - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - accentuated first sound; doubling of first sound; Graham Steel''s murmur.</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - straightening of left cardiac border; double contour of right border.</li></ul><h3>Mitral regurgitation :</h3><ul><li>Cough - positive</li><li>Haemolysis or bloody sputum - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - high-pitched blowing decrescendo diastolic murmur; Dureziez murmur.</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - enlargement of left atrium and left ventricle</li></ul><h3>Aortic stenosis :</h3><ul><li>Chest pain - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - gallop rhythm, loud systolic murmur at aortic area; diminished or absent second aortic sound</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - calcified aortic cusps and left ventricular enlargement</li></ul><h3>Aortic regurgitation :</h3><ul><li>Chest pain - positive</li><li>Chest sounds - Austin Flint murmur; Cole-Cecil murmur; blowing decrescendo diastolic</li><li>Chest X-ray findings - aortic dilatation and left ventricular enlargement</li></ul><h2>EXAMINATION</h2><h3>Inspection:</h3><ul><li>Cyanosis observes from the fingertips (peripheral) or in the mucous membranes (central) - severe underlying disease</li><li>Decreased consciousness level -  life-threatening situation, metabolic acidosis (diabetic ketoacidosis)</li><li>Kyphosis severe enough to cause dyspnoea should be evident</li><li>Patients with COPD - barrel-chested and cyanosed ot thin and tachypnoeic (with pursed-lip breathing) accompanied by the prominent use of the accessory musculature</li></ul><h3>Pluse:</h3><ul><li>A change in rate or regularity of rhythm - arrhythmia</li></ul><h3>JVP:</h3><ul><li>Acute elevation of the JVP - tension pneumothorax, pulmonary embolism or tricuspid regurgitation (prominent v waves)</li><li>Chronic elevation - congestive heart failure or any chronic lung disease with right heart failure (cor pulmonale)</li></ul><h3>Temperature:</h3><ul><li>Elevated temperature with a chest infection and pulmonary embolism</li></ul><h3>Trachea:</h3><ul><li>Deviates away from the side of a tension pneumothorax, pleural effusion and any large mass</li><li>Deviates to the side of a collapsed segment - obstruction of the bronchial lumen from tumour or foreign bodies</li></ul><h3>Expansion:</h3><ul><li>Reduced on the side of an area of consolidation (infection), pheumothorax and effusion, may be reduced bilaterlly in patients with COPD</li></ul><h3>Percussion:</h3><ul><li>Area overlying consolidation, effusion or collapse - dull to percussion</li><li>Hyperresonance - affected side of a pheumothorax (relative dullness of the unaffected side is the usual initial finding)</li></ul><h3>Auscultation of the precordium:</h3><ul><li>Murmurs associated with valvular heart disease</li><li>Presence of a third heart sound - cardiac failure</li><li>Quiet heart sounds - overexpanded chest from COPD</li></ul><h3>Breath sounds:</h3><ul><li>Localised reduction in the intensity over areas with consolidation or collapse of the lung</li><li>It may be reduced generally with asthma and COPD</li></ul><h3>Added sounds:</h3><ul><li>Wheezing in a localised area - intraluminal airway obstruction from inhaled foreign body or tumour</li><li>Generalised wheezing - asthma</li><li>When a history of preexisting asthma is not evident, then consider anaphylaxis</li><li>Localised crepitations over areas of pulmonary consolidation</li><li>Extensive bilateral crepitations occur with fibrosing alveolitis (fine inspiratory), pulmonary oedema and bronchopneumonia</li></ul><h3>Exercise tolerance abnormal:</h3><h3>Normal heart size with evidence of lung diseases:</h3><ul><li>Chest wall causes</li><li>Chronic airway limitations</li><li>Pneumothorad, hemothorax, hydrothorax</li><li>Mass (biopsy)</li><li>Infiltrative process - culture, bronchoscopy</li></ul><h3>Normal heart size normal lungs:</h3><ul><li>Normal  - anxiety (consider ECG)</li><li>Abnormal - consider scan, pulmonary angiography, neuromuscular evaluation</li></ul><h3>Enlarged heart:</h3><ul><li>LV dysfunction - ischemia</li><li>Pericardial effusion</li><li>Thickened pericardium</li><li>Valvular heart disease</li></ul><h2>INVESTIGATIONS</h2><h3>FBC:</h3><ul><li>Hb decreased - anaemia</li><li>Hb increased (polycythaemia) - chronic lung disease</li><li>WCC increased - infection, pulmonary embolism</li></ul><h3>Peak expiratory flow rate:</h3><ul><li>A reduced flow rate - asthma or chronic airflow limitation</li></ul><h3>ECG:</h3><ul><li>Arrhythmias are readily appreciated on the ECG</li><li>Atrial fibrillation or supraventricular tachycardia may precipitate dydpnoea in patients with preexisting heart or lung  disease</li><li>Arrhythmia may be a manifestation of  myocardial infarction, pulmonary embolism and hypoxia</li><li>Myocardial infaction - ST segment elevations</li><li>Pulmonary embolism - non-specific finding</li><li>Right bundle- branch block may - long-standing lung disease</li></ul><h3>Pluse oximetry:</h3><ul><li>Acute severe impairment of oxygen saturation - pulmonary embolus and pneumothorax</li><li>Postexercise desaturation helpful if  opportunistic pneumonia is suspected</li></ul><h3>ABGs :</h3><ul><li>Low levels  of bicarbonate - metabolic acidosis such as diabetic ketoacidosis</li><li>An alkalosis (high pH) with low PCO2 and high PO2 - hyperventilation</li><li>CO2 retention  - chronic lung disease (type II respiratory failure) or may need  ventilation with coexisting hypoxia in asthmatics</li></ul><h3>Cardiac enzymes:</h3><ul><li>CK, CK-MB or cardiac troponin  elevated -  mayocardial infarction in the setting of acute left ventricular failure</li></ul><h3>Chest X-ray:</h3><ul><li>Hyperinflation of the lungs (if the hemidiaphrgam is below the seventh rib anteriorly or the twelfth rib posteriorly) -  emphysema, and from asthma</li><li>Areas of consolidation are seen on a plain film</li><li>Radiographic changes of a chest infection may lag behind in time with the clinical findings</li><li>Cardiac failure is appreciated by cardiomegaly, upper lobe diversion of the pulmonary veins, bilateral pleural effusions, Kerley B lines (1-2 cm horizontal lines in the periphery of the lung fields) and patchy pulmonary oedema</li><li>Pneumothorax - by identifying the line of the pleura and the absence of lung markings beyond it</li><li>Bronchial carcinoma - a hilar mass, peripheral opacity or collapse and consolidation of the lung due to airways obstruction</li><li>Sputum and blood cultures - if an infective aetiology (pneumonia, lung abscess) is suspected, preferably before antibiotics are adminstered</li></ul><h3>Respiratory function tests:</h3><ul><li>Spirometry</li><li>Flow volume loops indicate fixed airways obstruction (plateau in the expiration phase), due to foreing body or intraluminal tumour</li><li>Restrictive patternof ventilatory impairment with a normal FEV1 to FVC ratio and reduced vital capacity - pulmonary fibrosis, infiltrative lung disease and restriction of chest will motion</li><li>Obstructive pattern of ventilatory impairment with a reduced FEV1 to FVC ratio and a normal vital capacity - asthma, COPD, bronchiectasis and cystic fibrosis</li></ul><h3>Bronchoscopy:</h3><ul><li>Performed if a foreign body is aspirated</li><li>Intraluminal bronchial carcinomas may be visualised and biopsied</li><li>Allows collection of specimens for culture in the diagnosis of pneumonia</li></ul><h3>CT throax:</h3><ul><li>Complete visualisation of the throax by CT to eveulate masses of unknown aetiology, and for staging of bronchial carcinoma.</li><li>High-resolution CT is useful for evaluating pulmonary fibrosis</li></ul><h3>Echocardiography:</h3><ul><li>Indicated if cardiac failure or valvular heart disease suspected</li><li>A large pulmonary embolus - a finding of right heart failure and elevated pulmonary artery pressure</li><li>Elevated pulmonary artery pressures -  pulmonary hypertension causing dysponea (causes  are idiopathic, congenital heart disease,  any severe  lung disease and recurrent pulmonary emboli)</li></ul><h3>V/Q scan:</h3><ul><li>Majority of pulmonary emboli may be diagnosed by V/Q scanning</li></ul><h3>Pulmonary angiography:</h3><ul><li>Indicated if the V/Q scan is inconclusive due to preexisting disease, or when urgent interventions such as thrombolysis or thrombectomy are planned</li></ul>', 'D');
