(20, 'Dysrhythmias', '<h2>BRADYARRHYTHMIAS</h2><h3>They result from two basic mechanisms:</h3><ul><li>Disorders of impulse formation.</li><li>Disorders of impulse conduction</li><li>Bradyarrhythmias are slow rhythms, with rates of less than 60b.p.m, The significance of the bradycardia depends on the clinical setting and can</li><li>The need for emergent treatment is determined by the presence of symptoms associated with the bradycardia&mdash; for example, syncope, chest pain, shortness of breath, or decreased level of consciousness.</li><li>When treating bradyarrhythmias, consider underlying causes like myocardial infarction, drugs, and electrolytes.</li><li>Emergency cardiac pacing may be necessary if symptomatic bradycardia does not respond to medications</li></ul><h2>ETIOLOGY</h2><ul><li>Organic heart disease (myocardial ischemia or infarction, rheumatic heart disease, Lyme disease)</li><li>Infiltrative heart disease (sarcoid, amyloid)</li><li>Electrolyte abnormalities (hyperkalemia)</li><li>Drugs (beta-blockers, digitalis, calcium channel blockers)</li><li>Degenerative disease of the conduction system (aging)</li><li>Hypothermia</li><li>Hypothyroidism</li><li>Exaggerated vagal tone</li></ul><h2>CLINICAL MANIFESTATION</h2><h3>History:</h3><h3>Common symptoms include:</h3><ul><li>Near syncope or lightheadedness</li><li>Syncope or loss of consciousness</li><li>Chest pain</li><li>Shortness of breath</li></ul><h3>Physical Examination:</h3><h3>Common signs of bradycardia requiring immediate treatment include:</h3><ul><li>Hypotension (systolic blood pressure less than 90mmHg)</li><li>Pulmonary edema</li><li>Shock (cyanosis, pallor, altered mental status, clammy or dusky skin)</li><li>Congestive heart failure (elevated jugular venous pressure, pulmonary rales, dependent edema)</li></ul><h2>DIFFERENTIAL DIAGNOSIS</h2><h3>Disorders of impulse formation:</h3><ul><li>Sinus bradycardia</li><li>Sick sinus syndrome</li><li>Atrioventricular nodal bradyarrhythmias</li><li>Ventricular bradyarrhythmias</li></ul><h3>Disorders of Impulse Conduction:</h3><ul><li>Sinoatrial block</li><li>Atrioventricular conduction</li><li>First-degree AV block</li><li>Second-degree AV block</li><li>Third-degree heart block</li></ul><h3>DISORDERS OF IMPULSE FORMATION :</h3><h2>SINUS BRADYCARDIA</h2><ul><li>Supression of sinus node discharge rate</li><li>Less than  60 bpm</li><li>Normal</li><li>Normal (0.12-0.20)</li></ul><h2>QRS</h2><ul><li>Narrow (0.04-0.10)</li><li>Normal (athletes, during sleep, vagal stimulation)</li><li>Pharmacologic (beta-blockers, digoxin, Ca plus  channel blockers, narcotics)</li><li>Pathologic process (myocardial infarction/ischemia,  hypothermia, hypothyroid, increased ICP)</li></ul><h3>If symptomatic and signs of hypoperfusion:</h3><ul><li>Atropine</li><li>Elective pacemaker</li><li>May need immediate external or internal pacing</li><li>Group of disorders that manifests with both bradycardia and tachycardia in the same patient</li><li>Slow arrhythmias: Sinus bradycardia, sinus pause, sinoatrial block, atrial flutter</li><li>Fast arrhythmias: Atrial fibrillation, artial flutter, PSVT</li><li>Variable</li><li>Absent</li><li>Variable</li></ul><h2>QRS</h2><ul><li>Narrow (0.04-0.10)</li><li>Ischemic and rheumatic disorders</li><li>Mayocarditis and pericarditis</li><li>Cardiomayopathies</li><li>Rheumatologic disease</li><li>Metastatic tumours</li><li>Surgical damage</li><li>Elderly patients with HTN</li><li>Beta-blocker, calcimum channel blockers, and amiodarone may worsen the bradyarrhythmia</li><li>Most common indication for a permanent pacemaker</li></ul><h2>ATRIOVENTRICULAR NODAL</h2><h2>BRADYCARDIAS</h2><ul><li>May be physiologic escape when SA node fails to generate impluse</li><li>Usually 45-60 bpm</li><li>Inverted (if conducted in a retrograde mannner)-may appear before, during, or after QRS complex</li><li>Variable</li></ul><h2>QRS</h2><ul><li>Identical to inherent QRS morphology</li><li>The underlying disorder may be sinus bradycardia, sinus arrest, or AV block</li><li>Beta-blockers and digitalis may also be responsible</li><li>Atropine</li><li>Artificial pacing</li></ul><h2>VENTRICULAR BRADYCARDIA</h2><ul><li>A physiologic escape rhythm that arises in absence of stimuli from above pacemakers</li><li>30-45 bpm</li><li>Absent</li></ul><h2>QRS</h2><ul><li>Wide (more than 0.10)</li><li>The underlying disorder may be sinus bradycardia, sinus arrest, or AV block</li><li>Beta-blockers and digitalis may also be responsible</li><li>Atropine</li><li>Artificial pacing</li></ul><h3>DISORDERS OF IMPULSE CONDUCTION :</h3><h2>SINOATRIAL BLOCK AND ESCAPE RHYTHMS</h2><ul><li>Absent atrial depolarization</li><li>If escape is AV node 45-60 bpm</li><li>Absent</li></ul><h2>QRS</h2><ul><li>Narrow (0.04-0.10)</li><li>Cardiac ischemia or infarct</li><li>Hyperkalemia</li><li>Increased vagal tone</li><li>Phamacologic (beta-blockers, digoxin, calcium channel blockers)</li></ul><h3>If symptomatic and signs of hypoperfusion:</h3><ul><li>Atropine</li><li>Elective pacemaker</li><li>May need immediate external or internal pacing</li><li>Less than 60 bpm</li><li>Normal</li><li>Prolonged more than 0.20</li></ul><h2>QRS</h2><ul><li>Narrow</li><li>Normal variant in healthy young adults</li><li>Electrolyte (hyperkalemia, hypermagnesemia)</li><li>Pharmacologic (beta-blockers, digoxin, Ca plus channel blockers, narcotics)</li><li>Pathologic process (myocardial infarction/ischemia, hypothermia, hypothyroid, increased ICP, rheumatic fever, myocarditis)</li></ul><h3>If symptomatic and signs of hypoperfusion:</h3><ul><li>Atropine</li><li>Elective pacemaker</li><li>May need immediate external or internal pacing</li><li>Non-conducted P wave</li><li>Prolonging of PR interval until a P wave is completely blocked</li></ul><h2>QRS</h2><ul><li>Narrow</li><li>Electrolyte (hyperkalemia, hypermagnesemia)</li><li>Pharmacologic (beta-blockers, digoxin, Ca plus  channel blockers, narcotics)</li><li>Pathologic process (myocardial infarction (inferior)/ ischemia, hypothermia, hypothyroid, increased ICP)</li></ul><h3>If symptomatic and signs of hypoperfusion:</h3><ul><li>Atropine</li><li>Elective pacemaker</li><li>May need immediate external or internal pacing</li><li>Non-conducted P wave</li><li>Normal (0.12-0.20)</li><li>No prior lengthening of PR interval</li></ul><h2>QRS</h2><ul><li>Narrow or wide, depending on the site of block</li><li>Cardiac ischemia (anterior wall) or infarct</li><li>Hyperkalemia</li><li>Increased vagl tone</li><li>Pahrmacologic (beta-blockers, digoxin, calcium channel blockers)</li><li>This may progress to complete heart block; thus a permanent  pacemaker is indicated. Emergent cadiology consultation should be obtained.</li><li>AV dissociation with no relationship between P waves and QRS complexes</li><li>All atrial beats are blocked and the ventricles are driven by an escape focus distal to block</li><li>Atrial rate Unrelated to ventricular rate. Block AV node rate: 40-60 Block occurs infranodal rate less than 40</li><li>Conducted P wave</li></ul><h2>QRS</h2><ul><li>Narrow or wide, depending on the site of block</li><li>Cardiac ischemia or infarct (interior or posterior)</li><li>Pharmacologic (beta-blockers, digoxin, calcium channel blockers)</li><li>Lenegre''s disease: fibrous degenerative changes in the conduction system that results from aging.</li><li>Infectious and inflammatory processes: abscesses, tumours, infiltrative disease of mayocardium, sarcoid nodules, mayocarditis, and rheumatic fever</li></ul><h3>Treatment include:</h3><ul><li>Atropine</li><li>Epi</li><li>Dopamine</li><li>Elective pacemaker</li></ul><h2>TREATMENT OF BRADY ARRHYTHMIAS</h2><h3>Emergency treatment is required when:</h3><ul><li>The heart rate is less than 50bpm with clinical evidence of hypoperfusion - chest pain, shortness of breath, decreased level of consciousness</li><li>Bradyarrhythmias may progress to complete heart block.</li></ul><h2>TACHYARRHYTHMIAS</h2><ul><li>Tachyarrhythmias are fast rhythms, with rates greater than 100 beats per minute.</li><li>Symptomatic tachyarrhythmias are identified by chest pain, dizziness, shortness of breath, syncope, diaphoresis, or palpitations.</li><li>Tachyarrhythmias with evidence of hypoper-fusion should be treated emergently with synchronized cardioversion.</li></ul><h3>Common mechanisms include:</h3><ul><li>Enhanced cellular automaticity in a normal or ectopic site.</li><li>Reentry loops in a normal or accessory pathway</li></ul><h2>SINUS TACHYCARDIA</h2><ul><li>The sinus node pacing the heart at a rate more than 100 bpm with normal P waves and QRS complexes</li><li>Most often arises from sympathetic stimulation of the SA node</li></ul><h3>Conditions that drive the heart rate faster:</h3><ul><li>Pain</li><li>Fever</li><li>Anxiety</li><li>Drugs</li><li>Hyperthyroidism</li><li>Hypovolemia</li><li>Pulmonary embolism</li><li>Myocardial ischemia or infarction</li><li>Anemia</li></ul><h2>PAROXYSMAL SUPRAVENTRICULAR</h2><ul><li>Recurrent attacks of tachycardias usually with sudden onset and abrupt termination that originate from ectopic focus above the ventricles (atrial or junctional)</li><li>Generally caused by AV nodal re-entry or increased automaticity of an ectopic focus</li><li>Premature atrial or ventricular contractions</li><li>Myocardial ischemia or infarction</li><li>WPW syndrome-congenital accessory tracts</li><li>Electrolyte disturbances</li><li>Drugs-digitalis toxicity</li></ul><h2>JUNCTIONAL TACHYCARDIA</h2><ul><li>Supraventricular tachycardias arising from the atrioventricular junction</li><li>Generally produces a rapid sequence of QRS-T cycles that may be slightly widened</li><li>Causes include AV nodal re-entry or increased automaticity of an ectopic focus</li><li>Hyperthyroidism</li><li>Myocardial ischemia</li><li>Structural heart disease</li><li>Drugs</li><li>Alcohol</li></ul><h2>ATRIAL FRIBILLATION</h2><ul><li>A chaotic "irregularly irregular" rhythm caused by continuous, rapid firing of multiple atrial automaticity foci</li><li>Only an occasional atrial depolarization gets through the AV node to stimulate the ventricles, producing an irregular ventricular rhythm</li><li>Hypertension</li><li>Myocardial ischemia or infarction</li><li>Mitral valve stenosis or insufficiency</li><li>Cardiomyopathies</li><li>Hyperthyroidism</li><li>Pulmonary embolus</li></ul><h2>ATRIAL FLUTTER</h2><ul><li>Originates from an atrial automaticity focus producing atrial depolarization that occurs in rapid succession</li><li>Characterized by a series of identical "flutter waves" in rapid back-to-back sequence</li><li>Most impulses are blocked at the AV node, so conduction to ventricles rate is a fraction of atrial  rate (ex 2:1 block-atrial rate = 300 bpm, ventricular rate = 150 bpm)</li><li>Myocardial ischemia or infarction</li><li>Valvular heart disease</li><li>COPD</li><li>Cardiomyopathies</li><li>Hyperthyroidism</li><li>Pulmonary embolus</li></ul><h2>MULTIFOCAL ATRIAL TACHYCARDIA</h2><ul><li>Multiple ectopic atrial foci that have achieved enhanced automaticity</li><li>The P wave morphology varies beat to beat</li><li>Generally seen in elderly patients with chronic lung disease and hypoxemia</li><li>Chronic lung disease</li><li>Theophylline toxicity</li></ul><h2>VENTRICULAR TACHYCARDIAS</h2><ul><li>Series of three or more premature ventricular complexes (PVCs) in a row produced by an automaticity focus in the ventricles</li><li>Produces wide QRS complexes with no P waves</li><li>Myocardial ischemia or infarction</li><li>Cardiomyopathies</li><li>Drug toxicity</li><li>Hypoxia</li><li>Electrolyte abnormalities</li></ul><h2>SYNDROME</h2><ul><li>An abnormal connection between atria and ventricles through an accessory bypass tract&mdash; can be either a re-entry tachycardia or have normal sinus rhythm depending on direction impulse travels down accessory path</li><li>Reentry tachycardia appears similar to PSVT&mdash; impulse travels down AV node and up</li><li>Pre-excitation syndrome&mdash; impulse travels down accessory pathway and up AV node with the following characteristic</li><li>No "delta" wave present when tachycardia occurs because of ventricular depolarization by AV nodal reentry</li><li>"Delta" wave only present with NSR</li><li>Congenital cardiac defects</li><li>Cardiomyopathies</li><li>Rapid ventricular rhythm caused by a prolonged QT interval</li><li>Undulating rotations of the QRS complexes with constantly varying amplitudes gives a sinusoidal pattern</li><li>Anti-arrhythmic drugs (Class IA & 1C)</li><li>Tricyclic antidepressants</li><li>Myocardial ischemia or infarction</li><li>Electrolyte disorders-hypokalemia, hypomagnesemia</li><li>Congenital QT prolongation</li><li>CNS lesions - subarachnoid or intracerebral hemorrhage</li></ul><h2>VENTRICULAR FIBRILLATION</h2><ul><li>Disorganized depolarization and contraction of small areas of ventricular myocardium producing an erratic, rapid twitching of the ventricles</li><li>Totally disorganized rhythm with no '' effective ventricular pumping activity</li><li>Myocardial ischemia or infarction</li><li>Hypoxia</li><li>Hypothermia</li><li>Electrocution</li><li>Shock</li><li>Electrolyte abnormalities</li><li>Drugs - digoxin or quinidine</li></ul><h2>NARROW COMPLEX TACHYCARDIA WITH</h2><h3>REGULAR RHYTHMS :</h3><h2>SINUS TACHYCARDIA</h2><ul><li>100-160 bpm</li><li>Normal</li><li>No specific treatment is required but consider treating the underlying condition</li></ul><h2>PAROXYSMAL SUPRAVENTRICULAR</h2><ul><li>150-250 bpm</li><li>Peaked or inverted</li><li>Vagal maneuvers</li><li>Adenosine</li><li>Ca2 plus channel or beta blockers</li><li>Synchronized cadioversion</li><li>150-250 bpm</li><li>Buried within QRS or inverted following QRS</li><li>Unstable patients synchronized cardioversion</li><li>Stable patients - vagal maneuvers</li><li>Adenosine</li></ul><h2>WPW SYNDROME</h2><ul><li>150-250 bpm</li><li>Unstable patients synchronized cardioversion</li><li>Stable patients - vagal maneuvers</li><li>Adenosine</li><li>Ablation of accessory tract</li></ul><h2>ATRIAL FLUTTER</h2><ul><li>250-350 bpm</li><li>"Sawtooth" shaped</li><li>Unstable patients synchronized cardioversion</li><li>Stable patients - Ca2+ channel or beta blockers, or digoxin</li></ul><h2>JUNCTIONAL TACHYCARDIA</h2><ul><li>150-250 bpm</li><li>Inverted</li><li>Treat underlying disorder</li><li>If cause is digoxin toxicity, discontinue drug</li><li>Amiodarone, beta blocker, or Ca2 plus  channel  blocker</li></ul><h3>NARROW COMPLEX TACHYCARDIA WITH IRREGULAR RHYTHMS INCLUDES :</h3><ul><li>Multifocal atrial tachycardia</li><li>Atrial fibrillation</li><li>Atrial flutter with variable block</li></ul><h2>MULTIFOCAL ATRIAL TACHYCARDIA</h2><ul><li>100-200 bpm</li><li>Varies from beat to beat (requires 3 or more  differently shaped P waves with varying PR  intervals)</li><li>Treat underlying disorder</li><li>For decompensated lung disease, treat with oxygen and bronchodilators</li><li>Amiodarone, beta-blocker, or Ca2 plus channel  blocker</li></ul><h2>ATRIAL FIBRILLATION</h2><ul><li>350-450 bpm</li><li>Fibrillatory waves&mdash;  no distinct P wave</li><li>Unstable patients need emergent synchronized  cardioversion</li><li>Stable patients need rate control with Ca2 plus channel blocker</li><li>Beta-blockers or digoxin</li><li>Because of risk of intra-atrial thrombi and arterial embolism, patients with Afib of more than 2 days should be anticoagulated (coumadin), first, for 3 weeks before attempts at electrical or chemical cardioversion</li></ul><h2>WPW SYNDROME WITH ATRIAL</h2><h2>FIBRILLATION</h2><ul><li>Fibrillatory waves&mdash;  no distinct P wave</li><li>Unstable patients need emergent synchronized cardioversion</li><li>Stable patients need rate control with procainamide or amiodarone (Class I)</li><li>Do not use adenosine, digoxin, Ca2 plus channel or beta-blockers as they may increase ventricular rate</li></ul><h3>WIDE COMPLEX TACHYCARDIAS INCLUDES :</h3><ul><li>Ventricular tachycardia</li><li>Supraventricular tachycardia with aberrant conduction</li><li>Torsades de pointes</li></ul><h2>EKG</h2><ul><li>3 or more consecutive PVCs</li><li>Wide QRS in a regular, rapid rhythm with a constant axis</li><li>Unstable without pulse&mdash; defibrillate  (unsynchronized</li><li>Unstable with pulse-synchronized cardioversion</li><li>Stable&mdash; amiodarone, lidocaine, procainamide, or  sotalol</li><li>250-350</li></ul><h2>EKG</h2><ul><li>Undulating rotations, of the QRS complexes</li><li>Constantly varying amplitudes give a sinusoidal pattern</li><li>Treat underlying disorder&mdash;  replete magnesium and potassium</li><li>Temporary cardiac pacing or isoproterenol to shorten the QT interval and overdrive the rhythm</li><li>TCA overdose, sodium bicarbonate</li></ul><h2>EKG</h2><ul><li>Fine course zigzag</li><li>No P waves or QRS complexes</li><li>Immediate defibrillation (unsynchronized cardioversion)</li><li>If initial 3 attempts at defibrillation fail, CPR should be initiated and further defibrillations should occur after various intravenous drugs.</li></ul><h2>DIAGNOSTIC EVALUATION</h2><ul><li>ECG is the first diagnostic test</li><li>Ventricular rate - fast (more than 100bpm), slow  (less than 60bpm), or normal (60-100 bpm)</li><li>Rhythm - regular or irregular</li><li>QRS width - narrow (less than0.12 seconds) or wide (more than 0.12 seconds)</li><li>P wave - present or absent and its relationship to the QRS complexes.</li></ul>', 'D'),
(21, 'Dysuria', '<ul><li>Frequency of micturition in elderly males especially nocturnal  - prostatitis</li><li>Frequency of micturition with pus discharge - gonorrhoea</li><li>Frequency of micturition with haematuria - cystitis</li><li>Frequency of micturition chronic with recurrent episodes of haematuria - tuberculosis, bladder</li><li>Frequency of micturition with colicky pain and haematuria - urinary tract infection</li><li>Frequency of micturition with fever - acute pyelonephritis</li><li>Frequency of micturition with uraemia - chronic pyelonephritis</li></ul><h2>CLINICAL CONDITIONS</h2><h3>Cystitis:</h3><ul><li>Pain and tenderness in hypogastrium with frequency, hematuria and dysuria</li></ul><h3>Gonorrhoea:</h3><ul><li>Burning on micturition with dysuria, with a history of sexual contact</li></ul><h3>Acute pyelonephritis:</h3><ul><li>Pain in loin along with dysuria, strangury, fever, rigor, nausea and vomiting</li></ul><h3>Chronic pyelonephritis:</h3><ul><li>Frequency of micturition, dysuria and lumbar pain with fatigue, nausea, vomiting and dyspepsia</li></ul><h3>Nephrolithiasis:</h3><ul><li>Renal colic with severe urethral pain with or without vomiting, intraabdominal distension, haematuria, frequency and urgency of micturition</li></ul><h3>Carcinoma of urinary bladder:</h3><ul><li>Dysuria, burning frequency of micturition and haematuria, pyuria and palpable suprapubic mass</li></ul><h3>Vulvovaginitis:</h3><ul><li>Burning during micturition with formication</li></ul><h3>Vaginitis:</h3><ul><li>Dysuria with vaginal discharge and dyspareunia</li></ul><h3>Cervicitis:</h3><ul><li>Vaginal discharge purulent with acute inflammation and dysuria with hematuria</li></ul><h3>Menopausal syndrome:</h3><ul><li>Frequency of micturition with incontinence and meatal tenderness</li></ul><h2>INVESTIGATION</h2><h3>Gonorrhoea:</h3><ul><li>Gonococcal culture - positive</li></ul><h3>Acute pyelonephritis:</h3><ul><li>Blood - leucocytosis</li><li>Urine - microscopy, numerous pus cells, red cells and fragments of renal tissue</li></ul><h3>Chronic pyelonephritis:</h3><ul><li>Blood urea - raised</li><li>Urine - pus cells, granular casts, epithelial cells.</li></ul><h3>Nephrolithiasis:</h3><ul><li>X-ray - radiopaque calculi</li><li>I.V.P.</li><li>Ultrasonogram</li></ul><h3>Carcinoma of urinary bladder:</h3><ul><li>Cystogram</li><li>Urogram - filling defect of bladder</li></ul>', 'D'),
(22, 'Ear ache', '<h2>CAUSES</h2><h3>Local:</h3><ul><li>Trauma - direct, haematoma</li><li>Boils</li><li>Inclusion dermoid</li><li>Malignant disease</li><li>Perichondritis</li><li>Chondrodermatitis nodularis</li><li>Furuncle</li><li>Malignant disease (rare)</li><li>Diffuse otitis externa, infective - bacterial, fungal, viral</li><li>Diffuse otitis externa, reactive - eczematous, seborrhoeic dermatitis, neurodermatitis</li><li>Malignant otitis extema</li><li>Necrotizing osteitis</li><li>Wax</li><li>Keratosis obturans</li><li>Foreign body - impacted</li><li>Trauma</li><li>Auricular haematoma</li><li>External auditory canal tumor</li><li>Otitis media - acute or chronic</li><li>Acute otitis media</li><li>Chronic otitis media - tubotympanic and</li><li>Mastoiditis</li><li>Serous otitis (rarely)</li><li>Malignant disease</li></ul><h3>Referred pain from inflammatory or neoplastic lesion:</h3><ul><li>Nasopharynx</li><li>Tonsil</li><li>Base of tongue</li><li>Larynx</li><li>Pharynx and hypopharynx</li></ul><h3>Referred pain:</h3><ul><li>Caries</li><li>Abscess</li><li>Impacted molar</li><li>Costen''s syndrome</li><li>Carcinoma of the posterior third of the tongue</li><li>Tonsillitis</li><li>Pharyngitis</li><li>Postoperative pain</li><li>Quinsy</li><li>Foreign bodies</li><li>Malignant disease</li><li>Osteoarthritis</li><li>Spondylosis</li></ul><h3>Neurological :</h3><ul><li>Herpes zoster</li><li>Glossopharyngeal neuralgia</li><li>Trigeminal neuralgia (occasional)</li></ul><h2>HISTORY</h2><ul><li>Wax, foreign bodies like pea, glass, piece of stick may be impacted in ear and cause pain which relieves after removal</li></ul><h3>Local:</h3><ul><li>Trauma - subperichondral haematoma due to shearing blow, present with brushing and a swelling</li><li>If the swelling  not drained, and repeated trauma occurs this will lead to the condition of ''cauliflower ear'' seen in rugby players</li><li>Cellulitis and swelling of the ear occur due to bites,  either animal or human</li><li>Swelling on the lobe of the ear - enquire about recent ear-piercing, as inclusion dermoids may result</li><li>Ulcers may arise on the pinna as a result of malignant disease, the most common being squamous cell carcinomas and rodent ulcers</li></ul><h3>External auditory meatus:</h3><ul><li>Irritation, discharge, pain and occassionally deafness, inflammation may spread out on the pinna</li><li>History of poking the ear with a matchstic or hair grip to remove wax, may occur in those who swim frequently at public baths</li><li>Furuncle (boil) in the external auditory meatus - extreme pain and throbbing, made worse by inserting an auriscope into the meatus</li><li>History of a foreign body inserted into the external auditory meatus - patient is most commonly a child, seeds or pips may have been inserted into the ear or  in adults it is often matchsticks, cotton-wool buds or paperclips that have been inserted to remove wax from the ear</li><li>Occassionally an insect gets into ear, usually with pain and discharge</li><li>Malignant disease of external auditory meatus - rare, intractable pain, bloodstained discharge, and may invade the middle ear, facial nerve or the temporomandibular joint when advanced</li><li>The patient may present with a facial palsy</li></ul><h3>Middle ear:</h3><ul><li>Acute otitis media - pain is intense and stabbing, may be fever and slight degree of deafness, inflammation or after bursting of the membrane and letting out of the pus, usually occurs in children, a history of common cold, tonsillitis, adenoiditis or infectious disease of childhood</li><li>In adults there may be a hisotry of sinusitis, trauma, air flight or temporal bone fracture, patient presents with severe earach, often with deafness, and appears flushed and ill.</li><li>Chronic otitis media - continuous discharge from ear with a history of deafness, discomfort in the ear, tinnitus giddiness and vertigo</li><li>Acute mastoiditis - a complication of otitis media, children still present with pain, discharge (creamy and profuse) and deafness, with swelling behind the ear, fever, tenderness on mastoid process</li><li>History of dental problems</li><li>Elderly - carcinoma of the posterior third of the tongue - elderly man spitting blood with a piece of cotton wool in his ear</li><li>Check for a history of tonsillitis or pharyngitis or difficulty in swallowing due to quinsy</li><li>Foreign body lodged in the pharynx may be responsible</li><li>Other malignant disease of the pharynx may cause referred pain</li><li>Check for a history of dysphagia</li><li>Herpes zoster of the geniculate ganglion give rise to lesions of the external auditory meatus, pinna and sometimes the palate</li><li>Glossopharyngeal neuralgia - very severe pain radiating from throat to tongue and into the ear</li></ul><h2>OTITIS MEDIA</h2><h3>Features:</h3><ul><li>Commonly seen in children</li><li>Deep, severe unilateral pain</li><li>Irritability</li><li>Restlessness</li><li>Fever</li><li>Poor feeding</li><li>Inflammed tympanic membrane and bulging</li><li>Decreased light reflex</li></ul><h3>Precipitating factor:</h3><ul><li>Upper respiratory tract infection</li></ul><h2>SEROUS OTITIS MEDIA</h2><h3>Features:</h3><ul><li>Commonly seen in children, early adults</li><li>Usually not painful</li><li>Decreased hearing</li><li>Crackling and gurgling sounds</li><li>Flud behind tympanic membrane</li><li>Decreased conductive hearing</li></ul><h3>Diagnosis:</h3><ul><li>Impedence tympanomety</li></ul><h2>OTITIS EXTERNA</h2><h3>Features:</h3><ul><li>Commonly seen in adults, diabetics, patients with seborrhoea, swimmers, often bilateral</li></ul><h3>Precipitating factor:</h3><ul><li>Pain on twisting pinna</li></ul><h2>BAROTRAUMA OTITIS</h2><h3>Features:</h3><ul><li>Severe pain</li><li>Upper respiratory infection</li><li>Nasal congestion</li></ul><h3>Precipitating factor:</h3><ul><li>Worse during descent of aircraft</li></ul><h2>MASTOIDITIS</h2><h3>Features:</h3><ul><li>Pain in and behind ear</li><li>Fever</li><li>Middle ear discharge</li><li>Pain and tenderness on mastoid process</li><li>Swelling behind the ear</li></ul><h3>Diagnosis:</h3><ul><li>X-Ray of mastoid</li></ul><h3>Features:</h3><ul><li>Commonly seen in children, adults</li><li>Vague pain or discomfort</li><li>Hearing impairement</li></ul><h3>Diagnosis:</h3><ul><li>Foreign body</li></ul><h2>REFERRED PAIN</h2><h3>Features:</h3><ul><li>Commonly seen in adults, increases with age</li><li>Rarely bilateral</li><li>Vertigo</li><li>Tinnitus</li><li>Jaw click</li></ul><h3>Precipitating factor:</h3><ul><li>Hot and cold foods may aggravate if dental in origin</li></ul><h3>Diagnosis:</h3><ul><li>Normal ear examination</li></ul><h2>EXAMINATION</h2><h3>Local:</h3><ul><li>Trauma - subperichondral haematomas</li><li>Bites will result in cellulitis and swelling of the ear</li><li>Inclusion dermoids follow ear-piercing and present as lumps in the lobe of the ear adjacent to the area  of piercing</li><li>Malignant disease - an ulcer, either with a typical appearance of a rodent ulcer ot the everted edges of a squamous cell carcinoma</li><li>Inflammation at the entry to the meatus</li><li>Meatus is tender and there is moist debris, oedema and redness of the meatal wall on examination with an auriscope</li><li>A furuncle (boil) is externally painful</li><li>Examination with the auriscope - tense, tender boil or even pus in the external auditory meatus</li><li>A foreign body is usually obvious on examination with the auriscope, as is malignant disease</li><li>Acute otitis media the patient is usually flushed and ill, often with a temperature of 39-40 degree,  tympanic membrane shows loss of lustre and distruption of the light reflex, redness, fullness and bulging of the drum. Signs of perforation with otorrhoea, with a mucoid, purulent or bloodstained discharge</li><li>Chronic otitis media - fluid in the middle ear (glue ear), with discoloration and often retraction of the tympanic membrane, Tunning-fork test will reveal conductive deafness</li><li>Acute mastoiditis - child is usually ill with a high pyrexia, tenderness over the mastoid process and postauricular swelling, tympanic membrane may be red and bulging or perforated with discharge</li><li>Examine for dental problems</li><li>Examine the posterior third of the tongue for carcinoma</li><li>Inspect the throat with a mirror looking for tonsillitis phryngitis, quinsy, foreign body to malignancy</li><li>Herpes zoster - vesicles in the meatus, on the pinna and sometimes on the palate and fauces, preceded by severe otalgia</li><li>Glossopharyngeal neuralgia - trigger areas in the throat in the same way as there is a trigger areas that may initiate trigeminal neuralgia.</li></ul><h2>INVESTIGATIONS</h2><h3>Hb:</h3><ul><li>Decreased - malignant disease</li></ul><h3>FBC:</h3><ul><li>Increased - acute otitis media., acute mastoiditis</li></ul><h3>ESR:</h3><ul><li>Increased malignancy and infection</li></ul><h3>Swab:</h3><ul><li>Culture and sensitivity</li><li>Otitits externa</li><li>Otitis media with discharge</li><li>Furuncle</li><li>Tonsillitis</li></ul><h3>Biopsy:</h3><ul><li>Malignant disease of the pinna and exteral audiatory meatus</li><li>Carcinoma of the posterior thirs of the tongue</li></ul><h3>Skull X-ray:</h3><ul><li>Opacity and coalescence of the air cells in mastoiditis</li><li>Malignancy</li><li>Mastoiditis</li></ul>', 'E'),
(23, 'Ear lumps, on or near', '<h2>BASAL CELL CARCINOMA</h2><ul><li>The raised nodule behind the ear shows the lustrous surface and telangiectatic vessels that suggest basal cell carcinoma, a slow-growing and common malignancy that rarely metastasizes. Ulceration may occur, and  in the absence of treatment extends in width and  depth. Like squamous cell carcinoma, basal cell  carcinoma occurs more frequently in fair-skinned people who have been much exposed to sunlight.</li></ul><h2>CHONDRODERMATITIS HELICS</h2><ul><li>This chronic inflammatory lesion starts as a painful, tender papule that is usually on the helix but may be on the antihelix. Typically the lesion is single, but in this case two are visible. The lower papule is an early lesion; the upper lesion illustrates the later stage of ulceration and crusting. Reddening may occur. Older men are usually affected. To distinguish chondrodermatitis from carcinoma, a biopsy is needed.</li></ul><h2>CUTANEOUS CYST</h2><ul><li>This cyst behind the ear used to be called a sebaceous cyst. It is a benign, closed, firm sac that lies in the dermis, forming a dome-shaped lump. It can be moved over underlying tissues but is attached to the epidermis. A dark dot (blackhead) may be visible on its surface. Histologically, one of two diagnoses is likely epidermoid cyst, which is common on the face and neck, and pilar (trichilemmal) cyst, which is common in the scalp. Each may become inflamed.</li></ul><h2>KELOID</h2><ul><li>A keloid is a firm, nodular, hypertrophic mass of scar tissue that extends beyond the area of injury. It may develop in any scarred area, but is most common on the shoulders and upper chest. A keloid on an earlobe that was pierced for earrings may be especially troublesome because of its cosmetic effects. Darker-skinned people are more likely than lighter ones to develop keloids. Recurrence of the growth may follow treatment.</li></ul><h2>LEPROMATOUS LEPROSY</h2><ul><li>The ear is one of the sites for lepromatous leprosy, a form of Hansen''s disease, which results from infection by Mycobacterium leprae. The multiple papules and nodules on this auricle are due to this chronic infection. Similar lesions would probably be visible on the face and elsewhere in the body. Other forms of the disease have different manifestations.</li></ul><h2>RHEUMATOID NODULES</h2><ul><li>In a patient with chronic arthritis, one or more small lumps on the helix or antihelix may be rheumatoid nodules of rheumatoid arthritis. Do not mistake such lumps for tophi. Additional nodules elsewhere, e.g., on the hands, along the surface of the ulna distal to the elbow, on the knees, and on the heels. Ulceration may result from repeated small injuries. Rheumatoid nodules may antedate the arthritis.</li></ul><h2>SQUAMOUS CELL CARCINOMA</h2><ul><li>Squamous cell carcinoma is most common in light-skinned people who have been frequently exposed to sunlight. This location on the helix and the raised, crusted border with central ulceration are both frequently seen. Biopsy confirms the diagnosis. A suture is present. A squamous cell carcinoma spreads locally. Occasionally it metastasizes, most often to regional lymph nodes.</li></ul><h2>TOPHI</h2><ul><li>A tophus is a deposit of uric acid crystals characteristic of chronic tophaceous gout. Tophi appear as hard nodules in the helix or antihelix and may discharge their chalky white crystals through the skin. Tophi may also appear near the joints, as in the hands, feet, and other areas. Tophi usually develop only after years of sustained high blood levels of uric acid. With better control of hyperuricemia by drugs, tophi are becoming less common.</li></ul>', 'E'),
(24, 'Eardrum abnormalities', '<h2>NORMAL EARDRUM</h2><ul><li>Normal right eardrum (tympanic membrane) is pinkish gray. The handle of the malleus lies in a somewhat oblique position behind the upper part of the drum. The short process of the malleus pushes the membrane laterally, creating a small white elevation. Above the short process lies a small portion of the eardrum called the pars flaccida. The remainder of the drum is the pars tensa. Anterior and posterior malleolar folds, which extend obliquely upward from the short process, separate the pars flaccida from the pars tensa, but they are often invisible unless the eardrum is retracted. From the umbo the bright cone of light fans anteriorly and downward. Posterior to the malleus, part of the incus is visible behind the drum. The small blood vessels that course along the handle of the malleus are within the range of normal and do not indicate inflammation. The ear canal, which surrounds the eardrum, looks flatter than it really is because of distortion inherent in the photographic technique</li></ul><h2>PERFORATION OF THE DRUM</h2><ul><li>Perforations are holes in the eardrum that usually result from purulent infections of the middle ear. They are classified as central perforations, which do not extend to the margin of the drum, and marginal perforations, which do involve the margin</li><li>The more common central perforation is illustrated. In this case a reddened ring of granulation tissue surrounds the perforation, indicating a chronic infectious process. The eardrum itself is scarred and no landmarks are discernible. Discharge from the infected middle ear may drain out through such a perforation, but none is visible.</li><li>A perforation of the eardrum often closes in the healing process. The membrane covering the hole may be exceedingly thin and transparent</li></ul><h2>TYMPANOSCLEROSIS</h2><ul><li>In the inferior portion of the left eardrum there is a large, chalky white patch with irregular margins. It is typical of tympanosclerosis: a deposition of hyaline material within the layers of the tympanic membrane that sometimes follows a severe episode of otitis media. It does not usually impair hearing, and is seldom clinically significant</li><li>Other abnormalities in the eardrum include a healed perforation (the large oval area in the upper posterior drum) and signs of a retracted, drum. A retracted drum is pulled medially, away from the examiner''s eye, and the malleolar folds are tightened into sharp oudines. The short process often protrudes sharply, and the handle of the malleus, pulled inward at the umbo, looks foreshortened and more horizontal</li></ul><h2>SEROUS EFFUSION</h2><ul><li>Serous effusions are usually caused by viral upper respiratory infections (otitis media with serous effusion) or by sudden changes in atmospheric pressure as from flying or diving (otitic barotrauma). The eustachian tube cannot equalize the air pressure in the middle ear with that of the outside air. Air is partly or completely absorbed from the middle ear into the bloodstream, and serous fluid accumulates there instead. Symptoms include fullness and popping sensations in the ear, mild conduction hearing loss, and perhaps some pain.</li><li>Amber fluid behind the eardrum is characteristic, as in this left drum of a patient with otitic barotrauma. A fluid level, a line between air above and amber fluid below, can be seen on either side of the short process. Air bubbles (not always present) can be seen here within the amber fluid</li></ul><h2>ACUTE OTITIS MEDIA WITH PURULENT EFFUSION</h2><ul><li>Acute otitis media with purulent effusion is caused by bacterial infection. Symptoms include earache, fever, and hearing loss. The eardrum reddens, loses its landmarks, and bulges laterally, toward the examiner''s eye.</li><li>In this right ear the drum is bulging and most landmarks are obscured. Redness is most obvious near the umbo, but dilated vessels can be seen in all segments of the drum. A diffuse redness of the entire drum often develops. Spontaneous rupture (perforation) of the drum may follow, with discharge of purulent material into the ear canal.</li><li>Moving the auricle and pressing on the tragus do not cause pain in otitis media as they usually do in acute otitis externa. Hearing loss is of the conductive type. Acute purulent otitis media is much more common in children than in adults.</li></ul><h2>BULLOUS MYRINGITIS</h2><ul><li>Bullous myringitis is a viral infection characterized by painful hemorrhagic vesicles that appear on the tympanic membrane, the ear canal, or both. Symptoms include earache, blood-tinged discharge from the ear, and hearing loss of the conductive type.</li><li>In this right ear, at least two large vesicles (bullae) are discernible on the drum. The drum is reddened, and its landmarks are obscured. Several different viruses may cause this condition.</li></ul>', 'E'),
(25, 'Eating disorders', '<h2>CAUSES</h2><h3>Commonest:</h3><ul><li>Transient disturbance of fad</li><li>Stress reaction</li></ul><h3>Common:</h3><ul><li>Anorexia nervosa</li><li>Bulimia nervosa</li></ul><h3>Rare:</h3><ul><li>Hypopituitarism</li><li>Diabetes mellitus</li><li>Thyrotoxicosis</li><li>Malignant disease</li><li>Tuberculosis</li><li>Malabsorption syndrome</li><li>Cerebral damage</li><li>Cerebral tumour</li><li>Kleine-Levin syndrome</li><li>Kluver-Bucy syndrome</li><li>Pyloric stenosis</li><li>Postgastrectomy</li><li>Habit disorder</li><li>Depression</li><li>Schizophrenia</li><li>Obsessive-compulsive disorder</li></ul>', 'E'),
(26, 'Elbow joint disorder', '<h2>CAUSES</h2><h3>Traumatic:</h3><ul><li>Supracondylar fracture of the humerus</li><li>Dislocation of the elbow</li><li>Pulled elbow</li><li>Fracture of the radial head</li><li>Fractured olecranon</li><li>Fractured epicondyle/condyle</li><li>Myositis ossificans</li></ul><h3>Degenerative:</h3><ul><li>Osteoarthritis</li><li>Osteochrondritis dissecans</li></ul><h3>Inflammatory:</h3><ul><li>Rheumatoid arthritis</li></ul><h3>Neurological:</h3><ul><li>Nerve entrapment - ulnar, posterior interosseous and median</li></ul><h3>Other:</h3><ul><li>Olecranon bursitis</li><li>Tennis elbow</li><li>Golfer''s elbow</li><li>Cubitus varus or valgus</li></ul><h2>HISTORY</h2><h3>Traumatic:</h3><ul><li>Supracondylar fracture  (fracture of childhood) - pain and swelling around the elbow after a fall on the outstretched hand</li><li>Dislocation of the elbow -  pain and swelling around the elbow</li><li>Pulled elbow (children aged 2-6 years) -radial head slipping out of the annular ligament due to swinging with the parents holding the hands</li><li>Fractures of the olecranon - due to fall on the point of the elbow or sudden contraction of the triceps</li><li>Myositis ossificans -  formation of calcified haematoma in front of the joint - limitation of movement of the joint, especially flexion after supracondylar fracture, dislocation of the elbow, ill-advised physiotherapy with passive stretching of the joints after trauma or after surgery</li></ul><h3>Degenerative :</h3><ul><li>Osteoarthritis of the elbow  - heavy manual workers or complicated fractures involving the joint</li><li>Osteochondritis dissecans - elbow pain, restricted movement due to loose body in the joint</li></ul><h3>Inflammatory :</h3><ul><li>Rheumatoid arthritis of elbow - signs of rheumatoid arthritis elsewhere, gross disorganisation of the joint with deformity, symptoms of ulnar nerve palsy</li></ul><h3>Neurological :</h3><ul><li>Nerve entrapment syndromes of ulnar, median or posterior interosseous nerves</li></ul><h3>Other :</h3><ul><li>Cubitus valgus may lead to ulnar nerve palsy slowly</li></ul><h2>OLECRANON BURSITIS</h2><ul><li>Swelling and inflammation of the olecranon bursa may result from trauma or may be associated with rheumatoid or gouty arthritis. The swelling is superficial to the olecranon process</li></ul><h2>RHEUMATOID NODULES</h2><ul><li>Subcutaneous nodules may develop at pressure points along the extensor surface of the ulna in patients with rheumatoid arthritis or acute rheumatic fever. They are firm and nontender, and are not attached to the overlying skin. They may or may not be attached to the underlying periosteum. Although they may develop in the area of the olecranon bursa, they often occur more distally</li></ul><h2>ARTHRITIS OF THE ELBOW</h2><ul><li>Synovial inflammation or fluid is felt best in the grooves  between the olecranon process and the epicondyles on either side. Palpate for a boggy, soft, or fluctuant swelling and for tenderness</li></ul><h2>EPICONDYLITIS</h2><ul><li>Lateral epicondylitis (tennis elbow) follows repetitive extension of the wrist or pronation-supination of the forearm. Pain and tenderness develop at the lateral epicondyle and possibly in the extensor muscles close to it. When the patient tries to extend the wrist against resistance, pain increases.</li><li>Medial epicondylitis (pitcher''s, goiter''s, or Little League elbow) follows repetitive wrist flexion, as in throwing. Tenderness is maximal at the medial epicondyle. Wrist flexion against resistance increases the pain</li></ul><h2>EXAMINATION</h2><h3>Traumatic:</h3><ul><li>Swelling around the elbow joint and limitation of movement</li><li>Normal relationship between olecranon, medial epicondyle and lateral epicondyle in an equilateral triangle</li><li>Damage to the brachial artery, median or radial nerve</li><li>Relationship between olecranon, medial epicondyle and lateral epicondyle in an equilateral triangle - lost</li><li>Swelling around the elbow joint and limitation of movement</li><li>Damage to the brachial artery, median or radial nerve</li><li>Check the distal circulation</li><li>Assess median and radial nerve palsies</li><li>Fracture of the olecranon -  swelling and tenderness directly over the olecranon</li><li>Test the integrity of the ulnar nerve if there is damage to the medial epicondyle</li><li>Myositis ossificans - calcified mass in front of the elbow joint with limitation of flexion</li></ul><h3>Degenerative:</h3><ul><li>Osteoarthritis - thickening of the joint with loss of movement and crepitus</li><li>Osteochondritis dissecans - restriction in movement, crepitus and locking of the joint due to a loose body</li></ul><h3>Inflammatory:</h3><ul><li>Rheumatoid arthritis - swollen, disrupted joint with deformity in longstanding arthritis &#149;  Examine the integrity of the ulnar nerve</li></ul><h3>Neurological:</h3><ul><li>In the distribution of the median, ulnar and radial</li></ul><h3>Other:</h3><ul><li>Olecranon bursitis - fluid-filled swelling over the olecranon, exhibiting fluctuation and transillumination which may become red and tender with infection</li><li>Tennis elbow - tenderness over the lateral epicondyle, pain exacerbated by pronating the forearm while extending the elbow</li><li>Golfer''s elbow - tenderness over the medial epicondyle</li><li>Cubitus valgus - examine the integrity of the ulnar nerve</li></ul><h2>INVESTIGATIONS</h2><h3>FBC:</h3><ul><li>Hb decreased - anaemia of chronic disease, like rheumatoid arthritis</li><li>WCC increased - septic arthritis</li></ul><h3>ESR:</h3><ul><li>Increased - rheumatoid arthritis</li></ul><h3>Rheumatoid factor:</h3><ul><li>Rheumatoid arthritis</li></ul><h3>X-ray:</h3><ul><li>Fractures around the elbow</li><li>Dislocation of the elbow</li><li>Osteoarthritis</li><li>Rheumatoid arthritis</li><li>Osteochondritis dissecans with loose body</li><li>Myositis ossificans</li></ul><h3>Ultrasound:</h3><ul><li>Olecranon bursitis</li></ul><h3>Aspiration:</h3><ul><li>Gram stain</li><li>Culture and sensitivity - infection</li><li>Crystals - gout</li></ul>', 'E'),
(27, 'Epididymis swellings - inflammatory', '<h2>TUBERCULOSIS</h2><h3>History:</h3><ul><li>Previous tuberculous infection, especially urinary</li></ul><h3>Other signs and symptoms:</h3><ul><li>Cough, wasting</li><li>Evidence of phthisis in lungs</li><li>Tubercle bacilli in urine</li></ul><h3>Scrotum:</h3><ul><li>May be adherent behind</li><li>May have sinus discharging thin pus</li></ul><h3>Testes:</h3><ul><li>Usually normal</li></ul><h3>Tunica vaginalis:</h3><ul><li>Hydrocele in 30 per cent</li></ul><h3>Epididymis :</h3><ul><li>Nodular enlargement of globus minor, less commonly globus major or whole epididymis</li><li>Nodules, hard and very tender</li><li>Later break down to abscess, with sinus</li></ul><h3>Cord:</h3><ul><li>Oedema of cord</li><li>Vas may be thickened</li><li>Beading of vas esxcessively rare</li></ul><h3>Prostate and seminal vesicles:</h3><ul><li>Vesicle on affected side may be hard and tender</li></ul><h3>History:</h3><ul><li>Usually none</li></ul><h3>Other signs and symptoms:</h3><ul><li>Usually none</li><li>Urine may smell fishy and contain Esch. coli</li></ul><h3>Scrotum:</h3><ul><li>Normal</li></ul><h3>Testes:</h3><ul><li>Normal</li></ul><h3>Tunica vaginalis:</h3><ul><li>Normal</li></ul><h3>Epididymis:</h3><ul><li>No local nodules or much enlargement, but affected part hard and tender</li><li>Changes usually involve globus minor or whole epididymis, does not break down</li></ul><h3>Cord :</h3><ul><li>Normal</li></ul><h3>Prostate and seminal vesicles:</h3><ul><li>Normal</li></ul><h2>GONORRHOEAL</h2><h3>History:</h3><ul><li>Recent infection, with gleet, and pain on micturition</li></ul><h3>Other signs and symptoms:</h3><ul><li>Urethral discharge</li><li>Gram-negative diplococci -  other manifestations such as joints</li></ul><h3>Scrotum:</h3><ul><li>Red, hot, swollen and tender</li></ul><h3>Testes:</h3><ul><li>Normal, but outline obscured by surroundings</li></ul><h3>Tunica vaginalis:</h3><ul><li>Small hydrocele usually present</li></ul><h3>Epididymis:</h3><ul><li>Whole epididymis large, hard and broad, hot and tender</li></ul><h3>Cord:</h3><ul><li>Whole cord tender and swollen</li></ul><h3>Prostate and seminal vesicles:</h3><ul><li>Prostate may be hot and tender</li><li>Tenderness along vesicles</li></ul><h2>SEPTIC</h2><h3>History:</h3><ul><li>Recent catheterization or operation on bladder or prostate</li></ul><h3>Other signs and symptoms:</h3><ul><li>Pus in alkaline urine</li></ul><h3>Scrotum:</h3><ul><li>Red, hot, swollen and tender</li><li>May suppurate</li></ul><h3>Testes:</h3><ul><li>Normal, but outline obscured by surroudings</li></ul><h3>Tunica vaginalis:</h3><ul><li>Hydrocele or pyocele</li></ul><h3>Epididymis:</h3><ul><li>Globus minor or whole epididymis enlarged and broad; hot and tender</li></ul><h3>Cord:</h3><ul><li>Whole cord tender and swollen</li></ul><h3>Prostate and seminal vesicles:</h3><ul><li>Swollen and tender</li><li>Vesicles may be felt</li></ul>', 'E');
