(28, 'Epistaxis', '<h2>CAUSES</h2><h3>Local infection:</h3><ul><li>Vestibulitis</li><li>Rhinitis</li><li>Sinusitis</li><li>Trauma to Little''s area</li><li>Dryness of nasal mucosa like sex, drugs</li><li>Abnormal anatomy like septal deviations</li><li>Ulceration and excoriation</li><li>Nasal fracture</li><li>Nasal infections</li><li>Tumours of the nose and sinuses</li><li>Septal granulomas and perforations</li><li>Foreign bodies</li></ul><h3>Systemic infection:</h3><ul><li>Scarlet fever</li><li>Malaria</li><li>Typhoid fever</li><li>Coagulopathy - haemophilia, Christmas disease, von Willebrand''s disease, purpura, leukaemia</li><li>Hypertension</li><li>Drugs, anticoagulants, aspirin, cytotoxic drugs</li><li>Atherosclerosis</li><li>Hereditary haemorrhagic telangiectasis</li><li>Vitamin deficiency - vitamin C, vitamin K</li><li>Renal dialysis</li><li>Drying of the nasal mucus membrane</li><li>Trauma - nose picking, blunt injuries, fractures</li><li>Hypertension arteriosclerosis</li><li>Bleeding tendencies - associated with aplastic anaemia, leukaemiathrombocytopenia, liver disease, hereditary coagulopathies and Rendu - osier - weber syndrome</li><li>Most of the bleeding occurs from the plexus of blood vessels in anteroinferior septum (Kiesslbach''s area)</li></ul><h3>Risk factors:</h3><ul><li>Nose picking (trauma) - commonest cause</li><li>Foreign bodies</li><li>Forceful nose blowing</li><li>Rhinitis</li><li>Dried nasal mucosa</li><li>DNS (deviated nasal septum)</li></ul><h2>TREATMENT</h2><ul><li>Bleeding may be arrested by pinching the alae of the nose for 5 -10 minutes and the patient is asked to breath through mouth. If bleedings does''t stop, then the bleeding point should be searched and cauterized</li><li>Bleeding can also be stopped by applying pressure gauze - pack soaked in phenylephrine 0.25% and a topical anaesthesia (2% lidocaine), electrocautery can be used</li><li>In hypertension and arteriosclerosis - bleeding likely to occur in for posterior region, in the inferior meatus, difficult to control</li><li>In cases where conserative management fails ligation of the internal maxillary artery can be tried</li><li>Rendu - Osier - Weber syndrome - multiple bleeding points seen due to arterio - venous aneurysms in the mucus membrane, may lead to frequent bleeding and anaemia Septal dermoplasty reduces the episodes of epistaxis</li><li>Need for blood replacements may arise where Hb level is very low</li><li>Venous pressure is reduced in the sitting position, and leaning forward lessens the swallowing of blood.</li><li>Topical 4% cocaine applied either as a spray or on a cotton strip serves both as an anaesthetic and as a vasoconstricting agent</li><li>When visible, the bleeding site may be cauterised with AgNO3, diathermy, or electrocautery</li><li>When a site of bleeding is inaccessible, nasal packing is necessary. A properly placed anterior pack requires several feet of half-inch iodoform packing lubricated with bacitracin or petroleum ointment. The packing is carefully and systematically placed along the floor and then the vault of the nose</li><li>In all patients PT, PIT and platelets count may be done</li></ul>', 'E'),
(29, 'Erythema', '<h2>CAUSES</h2><h3>Localized erythema:</h3><ul><li>Boil</li><li>Herpes simplex</li><li>Herpes zoster</li><li>Impetigo</li><li>Erysipelas</li><li>Gout</li><li>Thrombophlebitis</li><li>Lymphangitis</li><li>Irritant (thermal, caustic, traumatic)</li><li>Allergic (allergic contact dermatitis)</li><li>Fixed drug eruption</li></ul><h3>Localized patterns of erythema:</h3><ul><li>Rosacea</li><li>Palmar erythema</li><li>Erythema ab igne</li><li>Livedo reticularis</li><li>Erythema annulare centrifugum (Lyme disease)</li><li>Erythema induratum (Bazin''s disease)</li></ul><h3>Generalized erythema:</h3><ul><li>Toxic erythema</li><li>Erythema multiforme</li><li>Erythema nodosum</li><li>Lupus erythematosus</li><li>Dermatomyositis</li><li>Measles</li><li>Rubella</li><li>Scarlet fever</li><li>Erythema infectiosum</li><li>HIV infection</li></ul>', 'E'),
(30, 'Euphoria', '<h2>CAUSES</h2><h3>Common :</h3><ul><li>Alcohol</li><li>Mania (bipolar illness)</li><li>Schizophrenia and schizoaffective illness</li><li>Cyclothymic personality</li><li>Early dementia (Alzheimer''s type dementia, multi - infarct)</li><li>Frontal lobe syndrome</li><li>Frontal tumours (meningioma)</li><li>Head injury</li><li>Corticosteroids</li><li>L-dopa</li><li>Bromocriptine</li><li>Benzhexol</li><li>Procyclidine</li><li>Antidepressants (tricyclics and MAOIs)</li><li>Amphetamines and other sympathomimetics</li><li>Cannabis</li><li>Cocaine</li><li>Hallucinogens (LSD, psilocybins, mescaline)</li><li>Phencyclidine and related compounds</li><li>Opioids (heroin, morphine, codeine)</li><li>Inhalants (many solvents and spray can propellants)</li><li>Sedatives, hypnotics, anxiolytics (benzodiazepines, barbiturates)</li></ul><h3>Less common :</h3><ul><li>Temporal lobe epilepsy</li><li>Multiple sclerosis</li><li>Hypothyroidism</li><li>Pick''s disease</li><li>Neurosyphilis</li><li>Mild hypoxia (high altitudes)</li></ul>', 'E'),
(31, 'Exophthalmos (Proptosis)', '<h2>CAUSES</h2><h3>Unilateral exophthalmos:</h3><ul><li>Orbital cellulitis</li><li>Cavernous sinus thrombosis</li><li>Pseudotumoiir</li><li>Lymphoma</li><li>Cavernous haemangioma</li><li>Lacrimal gland tumour</li><li>Peripheral nerve tumour</li><li>Meningioma</li><li>Mucocele</li><li>Metastatic and secondary tumours</li></ul>', 'E'),
(32, 'Extravasation of urine', '<h3>Superficial extravasation:</h3><ul><li>Occurs in neglected cases of complete rupture of bulbous urethra</li><li>Behind mid perineal point</li><li>Into thighs</li><li>Into inguinal canal</li><li>Into scrotum</li><li>Beneath superficial fascia of penis</li><li>Up into the abdominal wall beneath the deep layer of superficial fascia</li></ul><h3>Deep extravasation :</h3><ul><li>Extraperitoneal rupture of bladder</li><li>Intrapelvic rupture urethra</li><li>After suprapubic puncture.</li><li>Urine extravasates into the layers of pelvic fascia and retroperitoneal tissues</li></ul><h2>TREATMENT</h2><h3>Superficial extravasation:</h3><ul><li>Urgent surgery</li></ul><h3>Deep extravasation :</h3><ul><li>Drain the prevesical space (Cave of Retzius) and perform suprapubic cystostomy</li></ul>', 'E'),
(33, 'Eye deviation', '<h3>Strabismus or squint:</h3><ul><li>Deviation of the eyes from the normal conjugate position</li></ul><h2>NON PARALYTIC</h2><ul><li>Deviation is constant in all directions of gaze</li><li>Caused by an imbalance in ocular muscle tone</li><li>Caused may be heriditary, usually appears early in childhood</li><li>Convergent - esotropia</li><li>Divergent - exotropia</li><li>Cover - uncover test - in right monooular esotropia (convergent strabismus), corneal reflections are asymmetric</li><li>Cover left eye - right eye moves outward to fix on the light when left eye is covered (left eye although not seen because it is covered, moves inward to some degree)</li><li>Uncover  - left eye moves outward to fix on the light, right eye deviates inwards again</li></ul><h2>PARALYTIC</h2><ul><li>Paralytic  - deviation varies depending on the direction of gaze</li><li>Usually caused by weakness or paralysis of one or more or extraocular muscles</li></ul><h3>IIIrd cranial nerve (left) paralysis:</h3><ul><li>Looking straight ahead</li><li>Eye is pulled outward by the action of VIth nerve</li><li>Upward, downward and inward movements are impaired or lost</li><li>Ptosis and pupillary dilation may be associated</li></ul><h3>IVth cranial nerve (left) paralysis:</h3><ul><li>Looking down and to the right</li><li>Left eye cannot look down when turned inwards</li><li>Deviation is maximum in this direction</li></ul><h3>VIth  cranial nerve (left) paralysis :</h3><ul><li>Looking to the right side -  eyes are conjugate</li><li>Looking straight ahead - esotropia appears</li><li>Looking to the left - esotropia is maximum</li></ul>', 'E'),
(34, 'Eye lumps and swellings (in and around)', '<h2>CHALAZION</h2><ul><li>A chalazion is a subacute nontender nodule involving a meibomian gland. A beady nodule in an otherwise normal lid, it is usually painless. Occasionally a chalazion becomes acutely inflamed but, unlike a sty, usually points inside the lid rather than on the lid margin.</li></ul><h2>DACRYOCYSTITIS</h2><h3>(Inflammation of the lacrimal sac):</h3><ul><li>A swelling between the lower eyelid and nose suggests inflammation of the lacrimal sac. An acute inflammation (illustrated) is painful, red, and tender. Chronic inflammation is associated with obstruction of the nasolacrimal duct. Tearing is prominent, and pressure on the sac produces regurgitation of material through the puncta of the eyelids.</li></ul><h2>EPISCLERITIS</h2><ul><li>Episcleritis is a localized ocular redness from inflammation of the episcleral vessels. In natural light, vessels appear salmon pink and are movable over the scleral surface. Usually benign and self-limited, episcleritis may be nodular or only redness and dilated vessels.</li></ul><h2>PINGUECULA</h2><ul><li>A yellowish, triangular nodule in the bulbar conjunctiva on either side of the iris, a pinguecula is harmless. Pingueculae appear frequently with aging, first on the nasal and then on the temporal side</li><li>A painful, tender, red infection in a gland at the margin of the eyelid, a sty looks like a pimple or boil pointing on the lid margin</li></ul><h2>XANTHELASMA</h2><ul><li>Slightly raised, yellowish, well-circumscribed plaques in the skin, xanthelasmas appear along the nasal portions of one or both eyelids. They may accompany lipid disorders (hypercholesterolemia), but may also occur independently</li></ul>', 'E'),
(35, 'Eye pain', '<h2>CAUSES</h2><h3>Eyelids:</h3><ul><li>Blipharitis</li><li>Stye (hordeolum)</li><li>Meibomian cyst</li><li>Xanthelasma</li><li>Entropion</li><li>Ectropion</li><li>Trichiasis</li></ul><h3>Eye:</h3><ul><li>Trauma</li><li>Foreign body</li><li>Bacterial conjuctivitis</li><li>Viral conjuctivitis</li><li>Chlamydial conjuctivitis</li><li>Allergic conjuctivitis</li><li>Subconjuctival haemorrhage</li><li>Episcleritis</li><li>Scleritis</li><li>Corneal abrasion</li><li>Corneal ulceration (keratitis) - bacterial, viral, fungal</li><li>Iridocyclitis (uveitis)</li><li>Acute angle- closure glucoma</li></ul><h2>HISTORY</h2><h3>Pain:</h3><ul><li>Sudden onset of unilateral eye pain and lacrimation - foreign body</li><li>Infective conjuctivitis - soreness rather than true pain, congestion, photophobia, and a discharge which may be purulent or mucopurulent are also present</li><li>Blepharitis - a foreign  body sensation or grittiness</li><li>Allergic conjunctivitis (hayfever, acute allergy or atopy) - itching rather than pain</li><li>Severe pain - corneal abrasions, ulcers, angle-closure glaucoma, herpes zoster opthalmicus, uveitis and scleritis</li><li>Patients with the uveitis and scleritisexperience exacerbation of pain on palpating the globe</li><li>Stye - suppurative inflammation of an eyelash follicle, common and extremely painful</li><li>A meibomain gland resolve spontaneously or leave a pea-size swelling known as a chalazion</li><li>Entropion - rolling inwards of the lid margin, eyelashes irritate the conjunctiva and cornea, causing a painful red eye</li><li>Ectropion  - rolling outwards of the lid margin, usually results in a watery eye</li><li>Subconjunctival haemorrhages - spontaneous may present with impressive chemosis (soft-tissue swelling), they are not usually painful</li></ul><h3>Iritis:</h3><ul><li>Pain is a prominent feature and does not allow patient to sleep, congested eye, photophobia and lacrimation, affected pupil is smaller than normal and reacts sluggishly to light, may be sticky exudate</li></ul><h3>Acute glaucoma:</h3><ul><li>Increase in the intraocular tension specially after the age of 50, pain and tenderness of the eye vary with the severity of the attack, severe hemicrania, misty vision and seeing of rainbows or halo around bright lights with in a few hours</li><li>Loss of vision - progressive</li><li>Cornea - cloudy, muddy and not sensitive to cotton wool</li><li>Pupil - irregularly dilated and is frequently oval vertically</li><li>Pupil fails to accommodate and to react to light</li></ul><h3>Corneal ulcer:</h3><ul><li>Eye is painful an congested, photophobia and blepharospasm, watering of eye, floor of the ulcer readily stains with fluoroscein eyedrops</li></ul><h3>Retrobulbar neuritis:</h3><ul><li>Pain increased by movement of eyeball and is tender to slightest touch</li><li>Dental disorders may give rise to reflex pain of eye</li></ul><h3>Visual disturbance:</h3><ul><li>Corneal ulceration, uveitis and acute angle-closure glaucoma - associated with photophobia</li><li>Patients with gluacoma may perceive halos around lights due to corneal oedema</li></ul><h3>Discharge:</h3><ul><li>A purulent discharge - bacterial and chlamydial conjunctivitis</li><li>Allergic and viral conjunctivitis - discharge tends to be clear</li></ul><h3>Past medical history:</h3><ul><li>History of atopy or hayfever present in patients with allergic conjunctivitis</li><li>Previous herpes infection on the face - may be the only clue with dendritic corneal ulceration</li><li>Conjunctivitis, urethritis and arthritis form the triad of Reiter''s syndrome caused by Chlamydia trachomatis infection</li><li>History of contact lense use - patients may develop sight-threatening infections acutely</li><li>Scleritis - deeper and more severe inflammatory process compared with episcleritis, associated with connective tissue diseases, such as rheumatoid disease and SLE</li><li>Uveitis - associated with inflammatory bowel disease, psoriasis, ankylosing spondylitis and sarcoidosis</li><li>Orbital congestion may be seen in patients with thyroid disorders</li><li>Xanthelasma - fatty plaques in the skin of the eyelids, extensive of multiple xanthelasma abnormalities of cholestrol metabolism, diabetes or arterial disease</li></ul><h2>EXAMINATION</h2><ul><li>Visual acquity assessed with correcting  spectacles to pinhole, and documented with reference to a Snellen chart</li><li>Corneal ulceration, uveitis and glaucoma - referral</li><li>Swelling of the upper eyelid with redness - stye</li><li>Bead of pus apparent at the infected hair follicle</li><li>Upper eyelid is everted to inspect for meibomian  cysts and foreign bodies</li><li>Papillae (conjunctival elevations with a vessel in the centre) seen with allergic conjunctivitis, and follicles (collection of lymphocytes) may be visible with viral or chlamydial infection</li><li>Ectropion - lower eyelids is everted</li><li>Entropion lower eyelids is inverted, the eyelashes scartch the conjunctiva and cornea giving rise to red, watery eye</li><li>Trichiasis caused by irregular pointing lashes</li><li>Xanthelasma - fatty plaques in the skin of the eyelids, like masses of yellow opaque fat, not painful or tender</li></ul><h3>Inspection:</h3><ul><li>Foreign bodies on the surface of the eye</li><li>Areas of erythema assessed</li><li>Diffuse erythema, maximal in the fornices, - conjunctivits</li><li>Localised areas of segmental erythema - episcleritis</li><li>Erythema maximal near the limbus -  focal keratitis</li><li>Scleritis - a brawny red discoloration</li><li>Deep crimson-red area - subconjunctival haemorrhage</li><li>Marked erythema adjacent to the iris - ciliary flush and occurs with anterior uveitis and glaucoma</li><li>Ulceration of the cornea may not be visible without fluorescein staining. Infection may extend to the anterior chamber, and a collection of pus (hypopyon)  can present as a white fluid level</li><li>Loss of brightness of the cornea occurs with glaucoma due to corneal oedema</li><li>Pupil - examined and the resting position noted</li><li>Constricted pupil  - from ciliary spasm with uveitis and it rests in a fixed, semidilated position with glaucoma</li><li>Fluprescein in staining should be performed and the eye is then viewed with a blue filtered light, corneal abrasions or ulcerations glow green</li></ul><h2>INVESTIGATIONS</h2><h3>Swab:</h3><ul><li>Microscopy and culture and sensitivity for infective organisms - stye, bacerial, viral and chlamydial conjunctivitis</li></ul><h3>Rose bengal staining:</h3><ul><li>To assess dead or damaged cells -useful in outlining a dentric ulcer with herpes simplex infection</li></ul><h3>Blood glucose:</h3><ul><li>Infections are often associated with diabetes, as are Xanthelsma</li><li>Intraocular pressure measurements</li><li>Increased glaucoma</li><li>Uveitis</li></ul><h3>Corneal scrape:</h3><ul><li>For infective lesions</li></ul>', 'E'),
(36, 'Eyelid abnormalities', '<h2>ECTROPION</h2><ul><li>In ectropion the margin of the lower lid is turned outward, exposing the palpebral conjunctiva. When the punctum of the lower lid turns outward, the eye no longer drains satisfactorily and tearing occurs. Ectropion is more common in the elderly</li></ul><h2>ENTROPION</h2><ul><li>Entropion, more common in the elderly, is an inward turning of the lid margin. The lower lashes, which are often invisible when turned inward, irritate the conjunctiva and lower cornea. Asking the patient to squeeze the lids together and then open them may reveal an entropion that is not obvious</li></ul><h2>EPICANTHUS</h2><ul><li>An epicanthus (epicanthal fold) is a vertical fold of skin that lies over the medial canthus. These folds are also seen in Down''s syndrome and in a few other congenital conditions. They may falsely suggest a convergent strabismus</li></ul><h2>EXOPHTHALMOS</h2><ul><li>In exophthalmos the eyeball protrudes forward. When bilateral, it suggests the infiltrative ophthalmopathy of Graves'' disease, a form of hyperthyroidism. Edema of the eyelids and conjunctival injection may be associated. Unilateral exophthalmos may be due to Graves'' disease or to a tumor or inflammation in the orbit</li></ul><h2>HERNIATED FAT</h2><ul><li>Puffy eyelids may be caused by fat. It pushes weakened fascia in the eyelids forward, producing bulges that involve the lower lids, the inner third of the upper ones, or both. These bulges appear more often in elderly people but may affect younger ones</li></ul><h2>PERIORBITAL OEDEMA</h2><ul><li>Because the skin of the eyelids is loosely attached to underlying tissues, edema tends to accumulate there easily. Causes include allergies, local inflammation, cellulitis, myxedema, and fluid-retaining states such as the nephrotic syndrome</li></ul><h2>PTOSIS</h2><ul><li>Drooping of the upper lid. A weakened muscle, relaxed tissues, and the weight of herniated fat may cause senile ptosis Ptosis may also be congenital</li></ul><h2>RETRACTED LID</h2><ul><li>A wide-eyed stare suggests retracted eyelids - in this case, the upper lid. The rim of sclera between the upper lid and the iris. Retracted lids and a lid lag are often due to hyperthyroidism but may be seen in normal people. The eye does not protrude forward unless exophthalmos coexists</li></ul>', 'E');
INSERT INTO `disease` (`disease_id`, `disease_name`, `keynotes`, `basics`, `lab`, `treatement`, `diagnosis`, `sex`, `age`, `disease_index`, `other`) VALUES
(1, 'Abdominal aortic aneurysm', '<ul><li>Arterial aneurysm is defined as a permanent localized enlargement of any artery to more than 1.5 times its expected diameter</li><li>Indications for surgical repair aneurysm > 5 cm, rapidly enlarging, symptomatic, or ruptured</li><li>Acutely expanding aneurysms produce severe, deep back pain or abdominal pain radiating to back</li></ul>', '<p>Commonest site of aneurysm. Most of the aortic aneurysms are infrarenal a swelling in the umbilical region or epigastric region and with backache. Often they contain clotted blood, and they feel firm, non-compressible, fixed and tender. Majority of cases are due to atherosclerosis.</p><p>Expansile pulsation is the characteristic feature of an abdominal aortic aneurysm which is appreciated by palpating the swelling gently all around and they do not disappear in the knee elbow position</p><p>The femoral pulses usually normal (but thrombosis or rupture of the aneurym, giving rise to features of acute ischaemia)</p><p>Pressure effects venous oedema due to pressure on inferior vena cava, erosion of vertebrae</p><p>Aneurysms bigger than 6 cm are dangerous</p><p>When an aneurysm has leaked or ruptured the patient has the general signs of massive blood loss pallor, sweating, stertorous breathing, tachycardia and hypotension, together with abdominal tenderness and guarding.</p>', '', '<ul><li>Incising the aneurym and a dacron graft is sutured end to end inside the aneurysmal sac</li></ul>', '', 'm', 70, 'A', '<h2>COMPLICATIONS</h2><ul><li>Anterior rupture of aneurysm (20%) haemoperitoneum</li><li>Posterior rupture of aneurysm (80%) retroperitoneal haematoma</li></ul>'),
(2, 'Abdominal wall  structures, injury', '', '<p>Pain and bleeding from the wound and slight localised guarding. The patient has no specific symptoms and signs of vomiting, thirst and fainting. Pulse, respiration and blood pressure may be normal and general condition is good.</p>', '', '', '', '', 0, 'A', ''),
(3, 'Abdomino-pelvic injuries - closed ', '', '<p>Closed injuries are caused by compression force as in blow by fist or blunt instruments or crush injuries due to runover accidents and fall of a heavy object over the abdomen. No marks of wounds except superficial abrasions or contusion of skin and subcutaneous tissues. If the wound is present, it does not extend into the peritoneal cavity and if there is no marks of external injury, it is difficult to diagnose</p>', '', '<ul><li>Sudden hospitalization and appropriate care with regards to the intensity of the wound</li></ul>', '', '', 0, 'A', ''),
(4, 'Abdomino-pelvic injuries - open ', '', '<p>Caused by sharp cutting or pointed instruments, like knife, razor, bullet or missile. Presence of lacerated, incised or penetrating wound is invariably associated with its extension into the abdomen and so the peritoneal cavity is in direct communication with the environment.</p><p>The intra-abdominal organs may be injured by the penetrating wounds which may be present in the anterior abdominal wall, side walls, back of the abdomen, chest wall and perineum, gluteal and femoral triangle.</p>', '', '<ul><li>Surgery if needed</li></ul>', '', '', 0, 'A', ''),
(5, 'Abnormal  premenopausal bleeding', '<ul><li>Normal menstural bleeding lasts an average of 4 days (range 2 to 7 days) with a mean blood loss of 40 ml.</li><li>Blood loss of over 80 ml per cycle is abnormal and frequently produces anaemia</li><li>Excessive bleeding often with the passage of clots, may occur at regular menstrual intervals (menorrhagia) or irregular intervals (dysfunctional uterine bleeding)</li><li>When there are fewer than 21 days between the onset of bleeding episodes, the cycles are likely to be anovular</li><li>Ovulation bleeding, a single episode of spotting between regular menses, is quite common</li><li>DUB is usually caused by overgrowth of endometrium due to oestrogen stimulation without adequate progesterone to stabilize growth, this occurs in anovular cycles</li><li>Anovulation associated with high oestrogen levels commonly occurs in teenagers, in women aged late 30s to late 40s and in extremely obese women or these with polycystic ovary syndrome</li></ul>', '', '', '<ul><li>Premenopausal patients with abnormal uterine bleeding include those with submucous myomas, infections, early abortion or pelvic neoplasms. DUB can usually be treated hormonally progestins, which limit and stabilize endometrial growth, are generally effective</li><li>D and C is usually not necessary in women under 40 years of age</li></ul>', '', '', 0, 'A', ''),
(6, 'Acquired adrenogenital syndrome', '', '<p>A condition of adults that is acquired or congenital in which excessive output of adrenal androgenic hormones causes virilization. The effects depend on age.</p><p>Usual course chronic; progressive.</p><p>System (s) affected</p><p>Endrocrine system</p>', '', '<ul><li>Surgery</li></ul>', '', 'f', 0, 'A', '<h2>DIFFERENTIAL DIAGNOSIS</h2><ul><li>Idiopathic or familial hirsutism</li><li>Polycystic ovary</li><li>Ovarian tumours</li><li>Cushing syndrome</li><li>Acromegaly</li></ul>'),
(7, 'Gestational hypothyroidism', '<ul><li>Hypofunction of thyroid during pregnancy</li><li>Weight gain, cold intolerance, dry skin</li><li>Constipation, memory loss</li><li>Lethargy, slow thought, slowing up</li><li>Bleeding, periorbital or facial oedema</li><li>Eye brows, loss of outer two-thirds loss with or without deafness and chest pain</li></ul>', '<p>A rare condition associated with infertility or coma, miscarriage, still birth, premature labour or foetal abnormalities if left untreated</p><h3>Sex :</h3><p>Female only</p>', '', '', '', '', 0, 'G', '<h2>COMPLICATIONS</h2><ul><li>Coma</li><li>Miscarriage</li><li>Still birth</li><li>Foetal abnormality</li><li>Premature labour</li></ul><h2>ASSOCIATED CONDITIONS</h2><ul><li>Infertility</li></ul>'),
(8, 'Gestational jaundice', '<ul><li>Usually due to viral hepatitis, gallstones, Gilbert''s or Dubin Johnson syndrome</li><li>Pruritus especially of palms and soles and mild jaundice in the latter half of pregnancy</li><li>Abdominal pain</li><li>Jaundice</li><li>Headache</li><li>Vomiting</li><li>Pre-eclampsia</li></ul>', '<ul><li>Cholestatic jaundice of pregnancy:  Pruritus and mild jaundice in the latter half of pregnancy. Associated with increased risk of pre-term delivery, foetal distress and perinatal mortality.</li><li>Acute fatty degeneration of the liver. Rare. Usually occurs more than 30wk. gestation. Clinical: Mother develops abdominal pain, jaundice, headache and vomiting.</li><li>Pre-eclampsia:  Jaundice is associated with severe pre-eclampsia with or without HELLP syndrome.</li></ul><h3>&#149;   Complication of severe hyperemesis gravidarum:</h3><h3>Sex :</h3><p>Female only</p>', '', '<h3>&#149;   Cholestatic jaundice of pregnancy:</h3><p>Usually this involves monitoring of foetal welbeing with delivery at the 1st signs of foetal compromise.</p><h3>&#149;   Acute fatty degeneration of the liver:</h3><p>Admit for specialist care</p>', '', '', 0, 'G', '<h2>MEDICATIONS</h2><p>Contraindications</p><h2>PROGNOSIS</h2><p>Jaundice clears less than 4wk. after delivery but often recurs in future pregnancies (40%).</p><p>15-20% maternal mortality, 20% foetal mortality</p><h2>COMPLICATIONS</h2><ul><li>Preterm labour (60%)</li><li>Fetal distress (33%)</li><li>Stillbirth (2%)</li></ul><h2>SYNONYMS</h2><ul><li>Cholestatic jaundice of pregnancy</li><li>Intrahepatic cholestasis due to pregnancy</li></ul>'),
(9, 'Gestational renal disease', '<ul><li>Commoner pre-eclampsia</li><li>Renal failure mild to moderate</li><li>Volume overload</li><li>Polyhydramnios</li><li>Hypertension</li><li>Pre-eclampsia</li></ul>', '<ul><li>Mild renal failure:  Creatinine less than 125 micromol/l and no hypertension. 96% have successful pregnancies without adverse effect on underlying disease. Low perinatal mortality.</li><li>Moderate renal failure (Creatinine 125-275 micromol/l) and severe renal failure  (Creatinine more than 275 micromol/l):  maternal complications occur in up to 70% and pregnancy-related loss of renal function in approximately half (10% progress to end-stage renal failure). IUGR in 40% and pre-term delivery in 60%.</li><li>Women on dialysis:  Conception is uncommon. High rate of miscarriage and IUD 40-50% live birth rate. Mothers are prone to volume overload, polyhydramnios and severe exacerbations of hypertension with or without pre-eclampsia.</li><li>Renal transplant:  Risk of 1st trimester miscarriage is increased, but pregnancies that survive are more than 90% successful.</li></ul>', '', '<ul><li>Mild renal failure:  Creatinine less than 125 micromol/l and no hypertension. 96% have successful pregnancies without adverse effect on underlying disease. Low perinatal mortality.</li><li>Moderate renal failure (Creatinine 125-275 micromol/l) and severe renal failure  (Creatinine more than 275 micromol/l):  maternal complications occur in up to 70% and pregnancy-related loss of renal function in approximately half (10% progress to end-stage renal failure). IUGR in 40% and pre-term delivery in 60%.</li><li>Women on dialysis:  Conception is uncommon. High rate of miscarriage and IUD, 40-50% live birth rate. Mothers are prone to volume overload, polyhydramnios and severe exacerbations of hypertension with or without pre-eclampsia. Women need a 50% increase in duration and frequency of dialysis during pregnancy.</li><li>Renal transplant:  Risk of 1st trimester miscarriage is increased, but pregnancies that survive are more than 90% successful. Immunosuppressant drugs must be continued they are not harmful to the foetus. Pregnancy does not affect long-term survival of the transplanted kidney. Pelvic position of the transplant does not compromise vaginal delivery</li></ul>', '', '', 0, 'G', ''),
(10, 'Gestational rheumatoid arthritis', '<ul><li>Rheumatoid arthritis during pregnancy</li><li>Exacerbations may occur in the puerperium</li><li>Joint morning stiffness, swelling, pain on passive motion (symmetrical)</li><li>Joint heat, deformity</li><li>Fatigue, anorexia, malaise</li><li>Depression</li><li>Rheumatoid nodules</li><li>Lymphadenopathy</li></ul>', '<p>Rheumatoid arthritis is usually alleviated by pregnancy</p><h3>Sex :</h3><p>Female only</p>', '', '<ul><li>Deliver babies with heart block by caesarean section</li></ul>', '', '', 0, 'G', '<h2>MEDICATIONS</h2><p>Contraindications</p><h2>COMPLICATIONS</h2><ul><li>Congenital heart block is a rare fetal feature</li></ul>'),
(11, 'Gestational systemic lupus erythematosus', '<ul><li>A multi-system, autoimmune inflammatory condition exacerbated in pregnancy and puerperium</li><li>Arthritis, arthralgia, myalgia, tenosynovitis</li><li>Anorexia, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea</li><li>Skin lesions photosensitivity, facial ''butterfly'' rash, vasculitis, hair loss, urticaria, discoid lesions</li><li>Oral ulcers</li><li>Eye pain and/or redness</li><li>Lungs chest pain and/or shortness of breath, pleurisy, pneumonitis, effusion, fibrosing alveolitis</li><li>Anaemia, thrombocytopoenia, splenomegaly</li><li>Headaches and visual problems</li><li>Psychosis/delirium, depression</li><li>Kidney proteinuria, hypertension, glomerulonephritis, renal failure</li><li>Heart pericarditis, endocarditis</li><li>CNS infarction, fits, cranial nerve lesions</li></ul>', '<p>Varies from mild to severe and may be lethal (CNS and renal forms)</p><p>Renal complications may worsen and be associated with hypertension with or without pre-eclampsia, IUGR and oligohydramnios are common as is premature delivery. Foetal effects include neonatal lupus (from passively acquired maternal antibodies usually self-limiting skin rash).</p><h3>Sex :</h3><p>Female only</p>', '', '<ul><li>If planning pregnancy refer for review of drugs. Once pregnant refer for specialist obstetric care.</li><li>Planned pregnancy should be embarked on after 6 months stable disease without requiring cytotoxic suppression.</li></ul>', '', '', 0, 'G', '<h2>MEDICATIONS</h2><p>Contraindications</p><h2>COMPLICATIONS</h2><ul><li>Of those with SLE glomerulonephritis and a creatinine more than 130umol prior to conception only 50% achieve a live birth. Pre-eclampsia, oligohydramnios, and intrauterine growth restriction may occur.</li><li>Rarely the fetus may be affected by passively acquired maternal anti-Ro antibodies that can cause a self-limiting sunlight sensitive rash (usually face and scalp) for which no treatment is required, but more rarely can cause irreversible damage to the fetal heart conduction system causing congenital heart block (approximately 65% of these neonates requiring a pacemaker)</li></ul>'),
(12, 'Gestational thromboembolism', '<ul><li>Thromboembolic phenomenon exacerbated during pregnancy</li><li>Leg pain or swelling</li><li>Fever mild, unexplained</li><li>Chest pain</li><li>Dyspnoea</li></ul>', '<p>Six times morethan usual</p><p>Caesarean section, prolonged bed rest, previous thromboembolism, lupus anticoagulant are risk factors.</p><h3>Incidence:</h3><p>1:100 pregnancies (20-50% antenatal)</p><p>Pain or swelling in the leg, mild unexplained fever, chest pain or breathlessness</p><ul><li>Suspect DVT and/or PE in any woman who is pregnant or in the puerperium who has pain or swelling in the leg, mild unexplained fever, chest pain and/or breathlessness.</li></ul><h3>Sex :</h3><p>Female only</p>', '', '', '', '', 0, 'G', '<h2>MEDICATIONS</h2><p>Contraindications</p><h2>PREVENTION</h2><ul><li>Prophylaxis is required if a patient has a thrombophilia or past history of pregnancy or Pill-associated thrombo-embolism. Options are warfarin or heparin (prolonged use can cause osteopoenia, alopecia and thrombocytopoenia; epidural anaesthesia is contraindicated)</li></ul>'),
(13, 'Gestational trophoblastic disease (GTD)', '<ul><li>A range of proliferative trophoblastic abnormalities that can be benign (hydatidiform mole) or malignant (choriocarcinoma)</li><li>Hydatidiform mole (or molar pregnancy) accounts for approximately 80% of cases</li><li>Complete moles usually result from sperm fertilization of an empty ovum, have a chromosomal pattern of 46,XX, and are paternally derived</li><li>Incomplete (partial) moles result when a normal ovum is fertilized by two sperm (or a haploid sperm that duplicates its chromosomes), usually have a chromosomal pattern of 69,XXY, and contain fetal tissue</li><li>Molar pregnancy may progress to malignant GTD, including invasive moles (10-15%) and choriocarcinoma (2-5%)</li><li>Preeclampsia in the first trimester is pathognomonic for hydatidiform mole</li><li>First-trimester uterine bleeding (most common), hyperemesis gravidarum, preeclampsia-eclampsia at less than 24 weeks, uterine size greater than dates, and hyperthyroidism (HTN, tachycardia, tachypnea)</li><li>No fetal heartbeat is detected</li><li>Pelvic exam may reveal enlarged ovaries with bilateral theca-luteincysts and possible expulsion of grapelike molar clusters into the vagina or blood in the cervical os</li><li>Complete hydatidiform mole has a "snow-sform" appearance on pelvic U/S</li></ul>', '', '', '<ul><li>Dilation and curettage (D&C) reveals "cluster-of-grapes" tissue</li><li>Beta-hCG closely and prevent pregnancy for one year to ensure accurate monitoring</li><li>Chemotherapy and irradiation are highly successful for metastases (90%)</li></ul>', '', '', 0, 'G', '<h2>DIFFERENTIAL DIAGNOSIS</h2><ul><li>Normal pregnancy</li><li>Spontaneous abortion</li><li>Ectopic pregnancy</li><li>Preeclampsia</li><li>Placenta previa</li><li>Placental abruption</li><li>Multiple gestation</li></ul><h2>IMAGING</h2><ul><li>Chest X-ray lung metastases</li></ul><h2>COMPLICATIONS</h2><ul><li>Malignant GTD</li><li>Pulmonary or CNS metastases</li><li>Trophoblastic pulmonary emboli</li><li>Acute respiratory insufficiency</li></ul>'),
(14, 'Gestational trophoblastic neoplasm', '<ul><li>A woman early in the second trimester of pregnancy who presents with painless vaginal bleeding with a positive pregnancy test and often a uterine size/date discrepancy. She may also have severe nausea and vomiting, visual disturbances, preeclampsia, and proteinuria</li><li>Gestational trophoblastic neoplasia is a rare variation of pregnancy that in most</li><p>instances is a benign disease called molar pregnancy (hydatidiform mole). These</p><p>neoplasms are derived from abnormal placental (trophoblastic) proliferation.</p><p>Fewer than 10% of patients with molar pregnancy will develop persistent or</p><p>malignant disease</p><li>A complete mole contains no fetus and accounts for approximately 90% of all</li><p>molar pregnancies</p><li>An incomplete mole contains a fetus plus molar degeneration</li><li>Upon diagnosis, the level of beta-hCG is extremely high in molar pregnancy and can</li><p>help both to classify risk category and to serve as a sensitive tumor marker for</p><p>further follow-up</p><li>Failure of quantitative hCG levels to regress suggests recurrent benign gestational</li><p>trophoblastic neoplasia and/or malignant transformation to choriocarcinoma,</p><p>occurring in less than 10% of patients. Treatment for this is usually chemotherapy.</p><li>Recurrence rate of molar pregnancy is 2%</li><li>Uterine tumor arising from hydatidiform mole following abortion or during normal pregnancy</li><li>Persistent vaginal bleeding starting at 6-8 weeks</li><li>Nausea</li><li>Vomiting</li><li>Vagina passage of intact or collapsed vesicles</li><li>Pre-eclampsia or eclampsia in second trimester</li><p>Gestational trophoblastic disease (GTD) is a group of diseases including hydatidiform mole, invasive mole and choriocarcinoma.</p><p>Gestational trophoblastic neoplasm (GTN) generally refers to invasive moles and choriocarcinoma. GTN is classified as nonmetastatic when there is no evidence of diseases outside the uterus and as metastatic when there is any disease outside the uterus.</p></ul>', '<p>The tumor develops from placental tissue and usually arises from a noncancerous placental tumor called a hydatidiform mole</p><p>A choriocarcinoma may also occur after an ectopic pregnancy or rarely after childbirth or termination of pregnancy</p><p>Occasionally, the tumor may not develop until months or even years after pregnancy</p><p>Usual course slow onset, curable</p><p>Endemic areas Asia</p><h3>Incidence :</h3><p>1 in every 20,000 pregnancies</p><p>System(s) affected</p><p>Female reproductive</p><h3>Age :</h3><p>Affects females of childbearing age</p><h3>Sex :</h3><p>Females only</p>', '', '<ul><li>Hydatidiform mole:  removal of mole</li><li>Choriocarcinoma is usually treated with chemotherapy, whether or not the disease has spread to other organs.</li><li>Stage I chemotherapy with optional hysterectomy</li><li>Stage II chemotherapy with recommended hysterectomy</li><li>Stage III combination chemotherapy with optional hysterectomy</li><li>Stage IV combination chemotherapy with local radiotherapy plus optional surgery</li><li>Hysterectomy</li><li>Prompt surgical removal of the intrauterine contents. Patients must then be followed closely for at least 1 year with periodic pelvic examination and quantitative hCG levels</li></ul>', '', '', 0, 'G', '<h2>IMAGING</h2><h3>Ultrasound scanning :</h3><ul><li>Using a probe inserted into the vagina to look for a tumor</li></ul><h3>CT scanning of the abdomen:</h3><ul><li>To check if choriocarcinoma is confirmed and to know wheather the disease has spread</li></ul><h2>PROGNOSIS</h2><p>Good prognostic factors of metastatic GTN includes -</p><p>Poor prognostic factors include -</p><h2>COMPLICATIONS</h2><ul><li>Left untreated quick spread first to the walls of the uterus and then to other organs such as liver</li></ul><h2>SYNONYMS</h2><ul><li>Choriocarcinoma</li><li>Chorioadenoma destruens</li></ul>');
